13:12.558 --> 13:15.618
Our topic today:
What is capitalism?

13:15.661 --> 13:16.821
Capitalism?

13:16.862 --> 13:19.330
Well, why should there be
any question about it?

13:19.365 --> 13:22.823
Hasn't it given us the highest
standard of living in the world?

13:22.868 --> 13:25.598
We're free to try to make a profit,

13:25.637 --> 13:27.935
to just get by, or to fail.

13:27.973 --> 13:29.964
That's what capitalism is:

13:30.009 --> 13:32.500
a system of free enterprise.

13:32.544 --> 13:34.842
Now tell us what
"free enterprise" means.

13:36.115 --> 13:38.515
I went to see
my friend Wally Shawn,

13:38.550 --> 13:40.745
a playwright
and sometimes actor.

13:40.786 --> 13:42.310
Inconceivable!

13:42.354 --> 13:45.585
But Wally also studied
history and politics

13:45.624 --> 13:48.491
and even a little
elementary economics.

13:48.527 --> 13:52.793
Free enterprise
is a form of words

13:52.831 --> 13:55.561
that is intended
to conjure up in your mind

13:55.601 --> 14:00.538
a little town with different shops.

14:00.572 --> 14:03.507
And the guy who runs
the best shop

14:03.542 --> 14:06.033
has the most customers.

14:06.078 --> 14:08.478
There is the basis
of the capitalistic system:

14:08.514 --> 14:10.106
the profit motive.

14:10.149 --> 14:12.982
He's in business to make money.

14:13.018 --> 14:15.486
The original theory of capitalism

14:15.521 --> 14:18.513
is that it's a very clever way

14:18.557 --> 14:22.926
of society voting on what goods

14:22.961 --> 14:25.361
it wants made.

14:25.397 --> 14:27.228
What do you use this for?

14:27.266 --> 14:31.100
That's-- I could use that
for practically everything I ever do.

14:31.136 --> 14:34.799
You know, society votes.

14:34.840 --> 14:37.104
They like the way this guy

14:37.142 --> 14:39.838
makes ice cream.

14:39.878 --> 14:41.505
But the other guy,

14:41.547 --> 14:44.880
they don't like
his ice cream that much

14:44.917 --> 14:49.786
and they don't buy it,
so it fades out.

14:49.822 --> 14:52.450
It's on me.
That is a good fit.

14:52.491 --> 14:56.825
The basic law of life
is that if you have things,

14:56.862 --> 15:00.229
you can easily get more things.

15:00.265 --> 15:03.257
Very quickly, one guy can have

15:03.302 --> 15:05.998
5 times more
than anybody else.

15:06.038 --> 15:08.438
- Free enterprise.
- Competition.

15:08.474 --> 15:09.941
The profit motive.

15:11.944 --> 15:14.845
My dad, an assembly-line
worker at General Motors,

15:14.880 --> 15:16.541
bought and paid for our house

15:16.582 --> 15:20.245
before I graduated
from kindergarten.

15:20.285 --> 15:23.413
We had a new car
every 3 years.

15:25.457 --> 15:28.290
We went to New York
every other summer.

15:28.327 --> 15:31.296
That's me on Wall Street.

15:31.330 --> 15:33.230
And that's me
directing my first movie

15:33.265 --> 15:34.789
at the World's Fair.

15:34.833 --> 15:38.860
We went to Catholic schools,
we lived a good life.

15:40.639 --> 15:43.972
If this was capitalism,
I loved it...

15:44.009 --> 15:46.477
and so did everyone else.

15:46.512 --> 15:50.505
During these years
a lot of people got rich

15:50.549 --> 15:54.542
and they had to pay
a top tax rate of 90%.

15:54.586 --> 15:56.679
90%?

15:56.722 --> 15:58.553
Yep.

15:58.590 --> 16:03.152
But they still got to live
like Bogie and Bacall.

16:03.195 --> 16:05.527
And what did we do
with all their money?

16:05.564 --> 16:08.328
We built damns, bridges,

16:08.367 --> 16:12.167
interstate highways,
schools, hospitals.

16:12.204 --> 16:14.638
We even sent a guy to the moon.

16:14.673 --> 16:17.073
Things seemed to be going
in the right direction.

16:17.109 --> 16:20.169
Dad had a secure job
and Mom could work

16:20.212 --> 16:22.646
if she wanted,
but didn't have to.

16:22.681 --> 16:26.583
Middle-class families only needed
one income to survive.

16:26.618 --> 16:29.883
Our union family had
free health care and free dental.

16:29.922 --> 16:33.380
The kids could go to college
without getting a loan from a bank.

16:33.425 --> 16:37.054
Dad had 4 weeks
paid vacation every summer.

16:37.095 --> 16:40.929
Most people had
a savings account and little debt.

16:40.966 --> 16:44.732
And Dad's pension was set aside
where no one could touch it.

16:44.770 --> 16:48.763
It would be there for him
when he retired.

16:48.807 --> 16:52.868
We got all of this because
our main industrial competition

16:52.911 --> 16:55.436
had been reduced to rubble.

16:55.480 --> 16:58.142
Here's what the German
car industry looked like.

16:58.183 --> 17:01.619
And here's the Japanese
auto industry.

17:01.653 --> 17:03.746
I guess you could say
it's easy to be number one

17:03.789 --> 17:06.723
when you have no competition.

17:06.758 --> 17:09.318
Yes, of course
not everything was perfect.

17:09.361 --> 17:11.261
We didn't mind having to put up

17:11.296 --> 17:14.231
with a little bit of this
and a little bit of that...

17:16.835 --> 17:19.463
just as long as we could be
middle-class.

17:21.807 --> 17:25.503
And we could count on our kids
having it better than we had it.

17:25.544 --> 17:28.877
It sounded like
a good deal to us.

17:28.914 --> 17:33.078
Capitalism-- no one
ever had it so good.

17:40.959 --> 17:42.984
And then, right when
we were in the middle

17:43.028 --> 17:46.465
of this big love affair
with capitalism...

17:46.465 --> 17:48.933
The ABC Sunday Night Movie
"The Gambler"

17:48.967 --> 17:50.628
will continue in its entirety

17:50.669 --> 17:54.264
following this live report
from ABC News.

17:54.306 --> 17:59.175
We are at a turning point
in our history.

17:59.211 --> 18:01.475
Along came Debbie Downer.

18:01.513 --> 18:05.279
Too many of us now
tend to worship

18:05.317 --> 18:09.720
self-indulgence
and consumption.

18:09.755 --> 18:13.748
Human identity
is no longer defined

18:13.792 --> 18:17.523
by what one does,

18:17.562 --> 18:20.429
but by what one owns.

18:20.465 --> 18:22.126
This is not a message

18:22.167 --> 18:25.728
of happiness or reassurance,

18:25.771 --> 18:28.001
but it is the truth

18:28.040 --> 18:30.031
and it is a warning.

18:30.375 --> 18:32.043
What a bummer.

18:32.077 --> 18:35.205
It was time to bring
a new sheriff to town...

18:36.381 --> 18:38.849
one who knew how to act
like a president.

18:38.884 --> 18:42.547
He knew how to handle workers
who wanted a better wage.

18:44.890 --> 18:47.825
All right, mister, I guess you win.

18:47.859 --> 18:49.349
Or these annoying feminists

18:49.394 --> 18:52.158
whining about their
Equal Rights Amendment.

18:52.197 --> 18:54.665
Well, I can change that in a hurry.

18:56.368 --> 19:00.168
A man who knew
how to get the job done.

19:00.205 --> 19:03.732
Ronald Reagan
came out of the B movies

19:03.775 --> 19:07.939
to become the most famous
corporate spokesman of the 1950s.

19:07.979 --> 19:10.675
It's a transistor radio too.
Weighs only a few ounces.

19:10.716 --> 19:12.149
You can slip it
right into your pocket.

19:12.184 --> 19:14.550
Boraxo waterless hand cleaner
really cleans up for us.

19:14.586 --> 19:16.520
He had found his calling

19:16.555 --> 19:19.490
and Wall Street
had found their man.

19:19.524 --> 19:22.584
You see, the banks and corporations
had a simple plan:

19:22.627 --> 19:25.994
to remake America to serve them.

19:26.031 --> 19:27.623
But to pull it off would require

19:27.666 --> 19:30.692
electing a spokesmodel
for president.

19:30.736 --> 19:34.934
And on November 4th, 1980,
that's what we did.

19:34.973 --> 19:36.804
...that I will faithfully execute

19:36.842 --> 19:39.037
the office of President
of the United States.

19:39.077 --> 19:41.272
Ronald Ronald Ronald...

19:41.313 --> 19:43.543
Thank you.

19:43.582 --> 19:46.312
It was an historic moment

19:46.351 --> 19:49.115
because now corporate America
and Wall Street

19:49.154 --> 19:52.146
were in almost complete control.

19:52.190 --> 19:54.886
See that guy standing
next to the president?

19:54.926 --> 19:57.793
You know, the one
that looks like a butler?

19:57.829 --> 20:00.195
His name was Don Regan,

20:00.232 --> 20:02.496
the Chairman of Merrill Lynch,

20:02.534 --> 20:07.062
the richest and biggest
retail brokerage firm in the world.

20:07.105 --> 20:10.074
He took the key position
of Treasury Secretary

20:10.108 --> 20:13.976
so he could enact the tax cuts
that the rich wanted.

20:14.012 --> 20:16.310
Regan then became
White House Chief of Staff

20:16.348 --> 20:19.909
as the president started to fade.

20:19.951 --> 20:23.079
Then they should give the president
what 43 governors have,

20:23.121 --> 20:25.589
a line-item veto.

20:25.624 --> 20:26.885
And...

20:27.826 --> 20:31.087
You're gonna have to speed it up.

20:31.930 --> 20:35.093
Who tells the president
to speed it up?

20:35.133 --> 20:38.967
The man from Merrill Lynch,
that's who.

20:39.004 --> 20:43.464
Things in America would never
be the same again.

20:43.508 --> 20:46.944
The country would now be run
like a corporation.

20:46.978 --> 20:49.071
We're going to turn the bull loose.

20:52.517 --> 20:56.112
And 4 years later,
when Reagan ran for reelection,

20:56.154 --> 20:59.590
it was all smiley faces
and happy talk.

20:59.624 --> 21:02.149
I really feel that we're gonna
be better off in the long run.

21:02.194 --> 21:05.129
We're on the upward swing

21:05.163 --> 21:08.690
and the factories are working
much stronger than before.

21:08.733 --> 21:11.133
We're back on top.

21:14.673 --> 21:17.039
Actually, what Reagan presided over

21:17.075 --> 21:21.637
was the wholesale dismantling
of our industrial infrastructure.

21:21.680 --> 21:25.514
This was not done to save money
or remain competitive,

21:25.550 --> 21:27.609
as companies back then
were already posting

21:27.652 --> 21:31.053
record earnings in the billions.

21:31.089 --> 21:34.820
No, it was done
for short-term profits...

21:38.930 --> 21:41.831
and to destroy the unions.

21:41.867 --> 21:44.961
Millions of people
were thrown out of work

21:45.003 --> 21:48.336
and the remaining workers
were told to work twice as hard.

21:49.808 --> 21:53.266
But wages for working people
remained frozen.

21:55.180 --> 21:58.013
The richest Americans
had their top income tax rate

21:58.049 --> 22:00.984
cut in half.

22:02.821 --> 22:05.915
Instead of being paid
a decent wage,

22:05.957 --> 22:08.721
we were encouraged
to live on borrowed money

22:08.760 --> 22:12.821
until our household debt
was nearly 100% of the GDP.

22:12.864 --> 22:16.027
There was an explosion
of personal bankruptcies.

22:16.067 --> 22:19.935
We found it necessary to lock up
millions of our citizens.

22:19.971 --> 22:22.269
Sales of antidepressants
skyrocketed

22:22.307 --> 22:24.901
as insurance
and pharmaceutical company greed

22:24.943 --> 22:28.140
pushed the cost
of healthcare up and up.

22:28.179 --> 22:31.706
All of this was great news
for the stock market

22:31.750 --> 22:34.810
and for America's CEOs.

22:39.824 --> 22:41.519
Half of Flint was now receiving

22:41.560 --> 22:44.723
some form
of government welfare.

22:44.763 --> 22:46.628
During the end
of the Reagan years,

22:46.665 --> 22:49.896
I made my first movie about
what had happened to the country

22:49.935 --> 22:53.393
and specifically to my hometown
of Flint, Michigan,

22:53.438 --> 22:56.669
the birthplace of General Motors.

22:56.708 --> 23:00.576
GM was posting profits
of over $4 billion

23:00.612 --> 23:02.603
while at the same time eliminating

23:02.647 --> 23:05.411
tens of thousands of jobs.

23:05.450 --> 23:09.386
I went to see GM's chief lobbyist
in Flint, Mr. Tom Kay,

23:09.421 --> 23:12.618
to ask him why
this was happening.

23:12.657 --> 23:15.649
General Motors wouldn't be doing
anybody any service

23:15.694 --> 23:17.161
if it goes bankrupt.

23:17.195 --> 23:18.958
It has to do what it has to do

23:18.997 --> 23:22.194
in order to stay competitive
in today's economic climate.

23:22.233 --> 23:26.294
Even if that means
eliminating 18,000 jobs?

23:26.338 --> 23:29.307
Even if it means
eliminating 20,000 jobs.

23:29.341 --> 23:31.639
- Or 30,000?
- Whatever.

23:31.676 --> 23:36.238
- How about all the jobs here in Flint?
- It could feasibly happen.

23:36.281 --> 23:38.841
And it did.

23:38.883 --> 23:41.681
Nearly all the jobs were eliminated

23:41.720 --> 23:44.484
and GM went bankrupt.

23:46.291 --> 23:49.920
Perhaps more distressing was the fact
that the rest of America

23:49.961 --> 23:54.091
was now starting to resemble
Flint, Michigan.

23:54.132 --> 23:58.296
But there were some cities
that still took pride in their greatness.

23:58.336 --> 24:00.099
<i>* Cleveland</i>

24:00.138 --> 24:02.629
<i>* Come on down
to Cleveland Town, everyone</i>

24:02.674 --> 24:05.575
<i>* Come and look
at both of our buildings</i>

24:05.610 --> 24:08.408
<i>* Here's the place where
there used to be industry</i>

24:08.446 --> 24:11.279
<i>* This train is carrying jobs
out of Cleveland</i>

24:11.316 --> 24:14.308
<i>* See the sun almost
3 times a year</i>

24:14.352 --> 24:17.116
<i>* This guy has at least 2 DUIs</i>

24:17.155 --> 24:20.090
<i>* Our economy's
based on LeBron James</i>

24:20.125 --> 24:22.958
<i>* Buy a house
for the price of a VCR</i>

24:22.994 --> 24:25.690
<i>* Our main export
is crippling depression</i>

24:25.730 --> 24:28.699
<i>* We're so retarded
that we think this is art</i>

24:28.733 --> 24:33.363
<i>* It could be worse, though,
at least we're not Detroit</i>

24:33.405 --> 24:35.600
<i>* We're not Detroit.</i>

24:35.640 --> 24:39.337
No, they're not Detroit.

24:39.377 --> 24:42.005
For 20 years I tried
to warn GM and others

24:42.047 --> 24:45.710
that this day was coming,
but to no avail.

24:45.750 --> 24:48.014
Maybe now they'd listen.

24:48.053 --> 24:50.487
So I went down to the headquarters
of General Motors

24:50.522 --> 24:54.185
one last time to share
some of my ideas.

24:54.225 --> 24:56.386
You don't have permission.
You can't film here.

24:57.462 --> 24:59.259
You don't have permission
from General Motors.

24:59.297 --> 25:01.891
- You can't film here.
- I'm just going up to see the chairman.

25:01.933 --> 25:03.924
No, sir.
No, sir.

25:03.968 --> 25:06.198
You know, I've been doing this
for, like, 20 years.

25:06.237 --> 25:07.727
I understand, sir.

25:07.772 --> 25:11.264
And I have not been
let into this building for 20 years,

25:11.309 --> 25:14.972
and I think it's about time
someone just let me in

25:15.013 --> 25:16.640
and let me talk to them.

25:16.681 --> 25:18.546
I've got some good ideas.

25:18.583 --> 25:23.020
4-7 to 7-6 Bravo Area Alpha.

25:23.054 --> 25:25.454
Go ahead.

25:25.490 --> 25:28.721
It's Michael Moore here
to see the chairman.

25:31.029 --> 25:33.554
Repeat that.

25:33.598 --> 25:35.691
It's the filmmaker
Mr. Michael Moore.

25:35.734 --> 25:37.725
He's here to see the chairman.

25:38.970 --> 25:40.562
- Gentlemen.
- Yes.

25:40.605 --> 25:43.005
You need to get prior permission.
You cannot film here, okay?

25:43.041 --> 25:45.771
But if I can't go in and get permission,
what am I supposed to do?

25:45.810 --> 25:48.301
I guess they're right.
Breaking up is hard to do.

25:48.346 --> 25:50.644
Stop that. Don't do that.
Just go in the building.

25:50.682 --> 25:53.378
For 35 years,
GM made more money

25:53.418 --> 25:55.511
than any other corporation.

25:55.553 --> 25:57.145
But eventually,
Germany and Japan

25:57.188 --> 25:59.986
rebuilt their car industry
and produced vehicles

26:00.024 --> 26:03.050
that were safer than ours,
more fuel efficient

26:03.094 --> 26:05.255
and rarely, if ever, broke down.

26:08.366 --> 26:12.735
In Germany, unions help hire and fire
the board of directors

26:12.771 --> 26:16.172
so the workers have a say
in what's going on.

26:19.043 --> 26:21.034
You see, the people
of Japan and Germany

26:21.312 --> 26:24.748
fight to make sure that even
their conservative political leaders

26:24.783 --> 26:26.910
don't destroy their middle class.

26:31.256 --> 26:33.884
So where exactly
are we right now?

26:33.925 --> 26:38.487
On the day that General Motors
declared Chapter 11 bankruptcy,

26:38.530 --> 26:41.966
I went with my dad to visit
the AC Spark Plug plant

26:42.000 --> 26:44.594
where he had worked
for over 30 years.

26:44.636 --> 26:48.299
- So you worked actually right here.
- You'd have to go--

26:48.339 --> 26:52.139
they had a ramp that took you
up over that, just beyond that...

26:52.177 --> 26:53.701
- Just beyond that space there?
- Yeah.

26:53.745 --> 26:55.736
- And then the factory was all over there?
- Yeah.

26:55.780 --> 26:58.180
The whole complex is, like,
2 miles long.

26:58.216 --> 27:00.548
I remember Mom bringing
us kids in to pick you up.

27:00.585 --> 27:02.485
- 2:30 every day.
- Yeah.

27:02.520 --> 27:05.546
You'd walk out of there,
right over in there in fact.

27:05.590 --> 27:07.558
And we'd be waiting
in the car for you

27:07.592 --> 27:10.083
and we'd see you
come down the ramp.

27:10.128 --> 27:13.723
We got real excited
every time we saw you.

27:13.765 --> 27:16.256
I was there 33½ years.

27:16.301 --> 27:17.960
33½ years?

27:18.403 --> 27:21.201
What's your best memory here,
being here, working here?

27:21.239 --> 27:24.402
My best memory?
I think the people.

27:24.442 --> 27:26.433
They were a really good bunch.

27:26.477 --> 27:29.344
- You liked the crowd you worked with?
- Yeah.

27:29.380 --> 27:32.645
A good place to work. I enjoyed it.

27:32.684 --> 27:35.551
But I'm sorry to see it go.

27:43.161 --> 27:45.891
Shortly before Christmas 2008,

27:45.930 --> 27:49.058
Republic Windows & Doors
in Chicago, Illinois,

27:49.100 --> 27:52.331
abruptly fired
its entire unionized workforce

27:52.370 --> 27:55.430
of over 250 people.

27:55.473 --> 27:58.931
They were given
only 3 days' notice.

27:58.977 --> 28:01.036
Bank of America
would no longer provide

28:01.079 --> 28:03.274
a line of credit to the company,

28:03.314 --> 28:07.410
and so the workers were not paid
the money owed to them.

28:07.452 --> 28:10.250
My life revolves around this job.

28:10.288 --> 28:14.452
I live according to my obligation
to my job, you know?

28:14.492 --> 28:18.553
And it's not just me,
it's all of the workers here.

28:18.596 --> 28:21.394
We go above and beyond

28:21.432 --> 28:24.026
the call of duty for Republic.

28:24.068 --> 28:26.798
And at the end,

28:26.838 --> 28:29.671
Republic cares nothing for us.

28:31.509 --> 28:34.478
We found out that they're gonna
shut the plant on Tuesday.

28:34.512 --> 28:37.743
We don't deserve what
they're doing to us, you know?

28:37.782 --> 28:41.081
It really hurts because,
like I said,

28:41.119 --> 28:43.087
this is my second family.

28:43.121 --> 28:45.715
So it was-- it really hurts.
It really hurts.

28:45.757 --> 28:49.659
I'm gonna miss
all of them, you know?

28:49.694 --> 28:52.663
I'm gonna miss them
and I don't think

28:52.697 --> 28:55.029
anybody on this planet

28:55.066 --> 28:58.297
deserves what they've done to us.

29:05.777 --> 29:07.836
Scenes like this
were being repeated

29:07.879 --> 29:11.940
all over the country,
and no one seemed to mind.

29:11.983 --> 29:14.383
<i>* Zambezi, Zambezi</i>

29:14.419 --> 29:17.047
<i>* Zambezi, Zam.</i>

29:17.588 --> 29:21.456
The president was enjoying
his final year in office.

29:21.492 --> 29:23.790
But as the economy
started to fall apart,

29:23.828 --> 29:27.958
he decided it was time
to roll out the C word.

29:27.999 --> 29:31.025
Capitalism is the best system
ever devised.

29:31.069 --> 29:32.468
Really?

29:32.503 --> 29:35.768
Voices from the left and right
are equating the free enterprise system

29:35.807 --> 29:39.470
with greed and exploitation
and failure.

29:39.910 --> 29:41.501
Greed,

29:41.546 --> 29:44.709
exploitation, failure?

29:44.749 --> 29:46.273
Go on, I'm listening.

29:46.317 --> 29:51.186
Capitalism offers people
the freedom to choose

29:51.222 --> 29:53.782
where they work
and what they do...

29:53.825 --> 29:56.521
Pat Andrews
has been looking for work.

29:56.561 --> 30:00.429
Every morning she scans
the classifieds in vain.

30:00.465 --> 30:02.228
There isn't anything in here.

30:02.266 --> 30:05.201
I'm not gonna be a gentleman's club
hired dancer either.

30:06.537 --> 30:10.029
...the opportunity to buy
or sell products they want.

30:10.074 --> 30:12.008
Tom Rendon has avoided layoffs

30:12.043 --> 30:14.705
at his sign company
in Stockton, California,

30:14.746 --> 30:16.646
all because this one word
now makes up

30:16.681 --> 30:18.740
for half his business.

30:18.783 --> 30:22.344
If you seek social justice
and human dignity,

30:22.387 --> 30:26.221
the free market system
is the way to go.

30:29.093 --> 30:32.221
And for those seeking
justice in Pennsylvania,

30:32.263 --> 30:36.165
free enterprise
was definitely the way to go.

30:39.670 --> 30:41.331
Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania,

30:41.372 --> 30:43.533
has one of the highest rates
in the state

30:43.574 --> 30:47.203
of young people locked up
in the juvenile home.

30:47.245 --> 30:49.577
Perhaps it's because
the good people here

30:49.614 --> 30:51.980
employ the practices
of capitalism

30:52.016 --> 30:55.247
in dealing with
their wayward youth.

30:55.286 --> 30:58.187
The county hired a private
profit-making corporation

30:58.222 --> 31:02.352
with a sweet-sounding name,
PA Child Care.

31:03.594 --> 31:06.529
It was owned and run
by 2 businessmen,

31:06.564 --> 31:11.228
one of whom was Robert Powell,
an attorney and entrepreneur.

31:11.269 --> 31:13.203
His good friend Judge Conahan

31:13.237 --> 31:15.603
closed down
the public juvenile home

31:15.640 --> 31:17.574
and then got
PA Child Care to build

31:17.608 --> 31:20.771
an $8 million
privately-owned facility

31:20.812 --> 31:22.712
and charge it back to the county

31:22.747 --> 31:25.443
for a mere $58 million lease.

31:27.385 --> 31:31.014
Let's meet some of Wilkes-Barre's
juvenile delinquents.

31:31.055 --> 31:33.353
Magee smoked pot
at a high school party.

31:33.391 --> 31:36.622
I was very rebellious
when I was at this age.

31:36.661 --> 31:39.459
Matt, he got into
an argument at the dinner table.

31:39.497 --> 31:42.159
I threw a piece of meat,
as in steak,

31:42.200 --> 31:44.668
cooked dinner,
at my mother's boyfriend.

31:44.702 --> 31:47.068
Jamie got in a fight
at a shopping mall

31:47.105 --> 31:48.367
with her best friend.

31:48.406 --> 31:51.842
I just figured, you know, we just weren't
gonna be friends anymore.

31:51.876 --> 31:54.401
And Hillary made
a MySpace page

31:54.445 --> 31:56.606
making fun
of her assistant principal

31:56.647 --> 31:59.138
for being strict and having
no sense of humor.

31:59.183 --> 32:02.619
And it said some pretty silly,
like, 14-year-old-girl stuff.

32:02.653 --> 32:06.384
Her assistant principal
called the police.

32:06.424 --> 32:10.724
They all appeared before
kindly Judge Mark Ciavarella.

32:10.761 --> 32:13.491
These kids were about
to get their first lesson

32:13.531 --> 32:15.499
in American capitalism:

32:15.533 --> 32:20.334
time is money, lots of money.

32:20.371 --> 32:23.670
I went in front of the court,
in front of Mr. Ciavarella,

32:23.708 --> 32:25.505
and I wasn't even in front of him
for 4 minutes.

32:25.543 --> 32:27.636
I was only in front of him
for, like, 2 minutes.

32:27.678 --> 32:31.307
The first thing that
Judge Ciavarella said to me was,

32:31.349 --> 32:34.216
"What makes you think
you can do this kind of crap?"

32:34.252 --> 32:36.686
I'm sure he knew in his mind
when I walked in

32:36.721 --> 32:38.484
that he was locking this kid up
no matter what.

32:38.523 --> 32:39.820
He didn't even look at me.

32:39.857 --> 32:42.826
Once I entered the courtroom,
I didn't have any chance.

32:42.860 --> 32:45.124
There was about 6 kids
who went in front of me.

32:45.163 --> 32:47.188
Every single kid who went
in front of Ciavarella,

32:47.231 --> 32:50.598
for all different reasons--
some minor, some serious--

32:50.635 --> 32:52.330
got sent away.

32:52.370 --> 32:56.272
Although Wilkes-Barre is located
in the United States of America,

32:56.307 --> 33:00.437
here capitalism
trumped democracy.

33:00.478 --> 33:03.709
Robert Powell, one of the owners
of PA Child Care,

33:03.748 --> 33:08.151
cut a business deal with Judge Conahan
and Judge Ciavarella.

33:08.186 --> 33:11.622
Judge Ciavarella then stepped up
his conviction rates.

33:11.656 --> 33:13.385
Many of these kids
were funneled

33:13.424 --> 33:18.191
into PA Child Care's
for-profit juvenile facility.

33:18.229 --> 33:19.628
And for their troubles,

33:19.664 --> 33:23.862
the judges received
over $2.6 million

33:23.901 --> 33:27.860
while the owners of PA Child Care
received tens of millions

33:27.905 --> 33:30.499
of taxpayer dollars
from the county.

33:30.541 --> 33:33.669
And where did Powell go
to enjoy all that money?

33:33.711 --> 33:35.906
On his private plane

33:35.947 --> 33:39.007
and his yacht,
the "Reel Justice."

33:40.685 --> 33:45.588
6,500 children
were unjustly convicted.

33:45.623 --> 33:49.024
It was good business
while it lasted.

33:50.161 --> 33:53.028
2 Luzerne County judges
in big trouble with the law.

33:53.064 --> 33:54.053
They're going to jail.

33:54.098 --> 33:55.531
Some kids were locked up

33:55.566 --> 33:59.832
even when probation officers
objected to detention.

33:59.870 --> 34:02.862
In there you lose track of time
and you lose track of the date.

34:02.907 --> 34:04.135
I was barely keeping track.

34:04.175 --> 34:07.303
It was supposed to be, like--
I believe it was, like, 2 months.

34:07.345 --> 34:09.745
And it went from 2 months
to 9 months.

34:09.780 --> 34:12.476
He said originally
3 to 6 months,

34:12.516 --> 34:16.509
but somehow I ended up
being there 11½ months

34:16.554 --> 34:19.387
and I never went back
in front of the judge at all

34:19.422 --> 34:21.050
for him to give me extensions.

34:21.092 --> 34:22.889
Not only did PA Child Care

34:22.927 --> 34:25.760
pay off the judges
to fill their cells,

34:25.795 --> 34:28.458
but their employees were the ones
who got to decide

34:28.498 --> 34:31.900
when a child had
enough rehabilitation.

34:31.936 --> 34:35.268
But that makes sense,
because any time a governmental unit

34:35.306 --> 34:37.866
turns over to
a profit-making corporation

34:37.908 --> 34:40.308
the duties it should be performing,

34:40.344 --> 34:42.369
what do you expect to happen?

34:42.413 --> 34:45.007
It makes me feel like
an item that they just used

34:45.049 --> 34:47.449
to just get money
and then tossed me aside.

34:47.485 --> 34:51.945
I'm just trying
to work on my flying

34:51.989 --> 34:54.184
and just trying to prepare
for my future

34:54.225 --> 34:57.456
so I can put this all behind me,
finally be done with all this.

34:57.495 --> 34:59.963
During the whole trial
I wasn't in control at all,

34:59.997 --> 35:02.431
but with flying it's only me.

35:02.466 --> 35:04.934
It's just that I just get
to do everything by myself.

35:04.969 --> 35:06.994
I'm the only one on the control.

35:07.038 --> 35:08.869
Matt loves to fly

35:08.906 --> 35:12.171
and hopes to become
a pilot someday.

35:12.209 --> 35:14.837
If he does,
he'll get his 2nd lesson

35:14.879 --> 35:17.473
in capitalism:

35:17.515 --> 35:20.541
that in America,
sometimes you're better off

35:20.584 --> 35:23.020
working at Mickey D's.

35:23.520 --> 35:25.580
Remember Sully?

35:25.623 --> 35:26.954
Captain Sullenberger,

35:26.991 --> 35:30.017
who safely landed an airbus
in the Hudson River

35:30.061 --> 35:32.287
saving the lives of 150 passengers?

35:33.930 --> 35:35.997
A true American hero.

35:39.136 --> 35:42.037
He met the mayor.
He went to the State of the Union.

35:42.073 --> 35:44.769
Heck, he even went
to the Super Bowl.

35:44.809 --> 35:47.039
And then he went to Congress.

35:47.078 --> 35:50.138
Flying has been my lifelong passion.

35:50.181 --> 35:52.342
But while I love my profession,

35:52.383 --> 35:55.079
I do not like
what has happened to it.

35:55.319 --> 35:57.212
It is my personal experience

35:57.254 --> 36:00.451
that my decision to remain
in the profession I love

36:00.491 --> 36:05.121
has come at a great financial cost
to me and to my family.

36:05.162 --> 36:07.426
My pay has been cut 40%.

36:07.465 --> 36:11.128
My pension, like most airline pensions,
has been terminated.

36:11.168 --> 36:14.695
So please do not think I exaggerate
when I say that I do not know

36:14.739 --> 36:18.038
a single professional airline pilot
who wants his or her children

36:18.075 --> 36:19.667
to follow in their footsteps.

36:20.210 --> 36:22.440
You cleared the room
with that one, Sully.

36:22.480 --> 36:24.778
I don't think the congressmen
wanted to hear that stuff.

36:24.815 --> 36:27.750
- They like you as a hero.
- The current experience...

36:42.333 --> 36:44.392
What was your starting pay as a pilot?

36:44.435 --> 36:46.733
I made $19,000 the first year.

36:46.771 --> 36:50.229
I was bumped up to about 22,000
or 23,000 the second year.

36:50.274 --> 36:52.902
Last year, gross pay

36:52.943 --> 36:55.377
I made $17,600.

36:55.413 --> 36:58.007
There's a joke in the airline
when we get our wings pinned on us

36:58.048 --> 37:01.506
as new-hire airline pilots
that the company just kinda says,

37:01.552 --> 37:04.316
"Hey, don't apply for food stamps
in your uniform."

37:04.355 --> 37:07.222
I don't know about you,
but I want the pilot

37:07.258 --> 37:11.058
who's got me 30,000 feet up in the air
to be paid really well

37:11.095 --> 37:14.155
and not sitting up in the cockpit
digging through the pilot's seat

37:14.198 --> 37:16.189
looking for loose change.

37:16.233 --> 37:18.201
There was a period
of about 4 months

37:18.235 --> 37:20.999
where I was on food stamps.

37:21.038 --> 37:22.528
- You were on food stamps?
- Yes.

37:22.573 --> 37:25.337
- And you were still flying the plane?
- Yes.

37:25.376 --> 37:27.742
With my--
with my food stamp card.

37:27.778 --> 37:30.542
The lady I talked to
in the food stamp office,

37:30.581 --> 37:33.516
when I told her I was a pilot,
she didn't bat an eye,

37:33.551 --> 37:35.883
but she didn't--
I knew she didn't believe me.

37:35.920 --> 37:38.548
How have you gotten by?
How have you been able to afford things?

37:38.589 --> 37:41.183
Relying on credit cards
to buy the groceries at times

37:41.225 --> 37:42.954
- when I wasn't on food stamps.
- Really?

37:42.993 --> 37:45.291
I have about $10,000
in credit card debt

37:45.329 --> 37:47.320
just on the necessities,

37:47.364 --> 37:49.924
not on the big-screen TV
and the stereo.

37:49.967 --> 37:53.164
You're using it to buy
your groceries and get by.

37:53.204 --> 37:55.138
- Yes.
- Do you have any student loan debt?

37:55.172 --> 37:56.867
- Yes.
- How much?

37:56.907 --> 37:58.465
Mine is about 80,000.

37:58.509 --> 38:01.910
- I took out $100,000.
- Student loans?

38:01.946 --> 38:04.813
And by the time I pay it back,
at this rate,

38:04.849 --> 38:07.215
it'll probably cost me well over
a half a million with interest

38:07.251 --> 38:09.811
and fees and penalties.

38:09.854 --> 38:12.084
It's something that I don't--
I don't like to spend a lot of time

38:12.122 --> 38:13.817
thinking about
because it's abysmal.

38:13.858 --> 38:16.326
It's one way that I get down
really quickly

38:16.360 --> 38:18.021
about my chosen career field

38:18.062 --> 38:20.496
is to think about how much I owe
and how little I make.

38:20.531 --> 38:23.432
Have you had to work
a 2nd job to make ends meet?

38:23.467 --> 38:25.833
I walk dogs on the side,

38:25.870 --> 38:29.067
I distribute MonaVie Juice.

38:29.106 --> 38:32.371
I have known pilots
to donate plasma

38:32.409 --> 38:34.240
for extra cash.

38:34.278 --> 38:37.145
- You mean they give blood?
- They-- well--

38:37.181 --> 38:39.809
So they can make extra money
even though they're flying an airplane?

38:39.850 --> 38:41.841
Yeah.
They donate their plasma.

38:41.886 --> 38:46.152
So they get the blood back,
but you can get paid for plasma.

38:46.190 --> 38:47.487
I see.

38:47.525 --> 38:49.322
They suck the blood out of you,
take the plasma...

38:49.360 --> 38:50.827
- Give you the blood back.
- ...give you the--

38:50.861 --> 38:52.726
Well then,
not such a bad deal.

38:52.763 --> 38:56.255
The only reason people stay flying
is because they love it.

38:56.300 --> 38:58.165
And managements
take advantage of that.

38:58.202 --> 39:01.535
The airlines
have managed to farm out

39:01.572 --> 39:05.975
a lot of the flying to commuters

39:06.010 --> 39:09.207
in an effort to basically
bust the unions.

39:09.246 --> 39:11.339
You can't compete

39:11.382 --> 39:15.614
to a lower and lower level
every year

39:15.653 --> 39:18.053
without skimping
on safety somehow.

39:20.357 --> 39:25.158
At approximately 10:15 PM
on February 12, 2009,

39:25.195 --> 39:27.925
Continental connection flight 3407

39:27.965 --> 39:30.559
began its descent
to the airport in Buffalo.

39:32.336 --> 39:34.201
Stand by, there's some
ground communication,

39:34.238 --> 39:36.138
either state police
or sheriff's department.

39:36.173 --> 39:37.868
We need to find out if anything
is on the ground.

39:37.908 --> 39:40.308
This aircraft was 5 miles out,
and all of a sudden

39:40.344 --> 39:42.175
we have no response
to that aircraft.

39:42.212 --> 39:45.204
All I could tell you is there was
an aircraft over the marker

39:45.249 --> 39:48.275
and we're not talking to them now.

39:48.319 --> 39:50.480
No one survived the crash

39:50.521 --> 39:53.456
and 50 people lost their lives.

39:54.992 --> 39:58.257
The media focused
on the actions of the pilots.

39:58.295 --> 40:01.355
Captain Marvin Renslow
and First Officer Shaw

40:01.398 --> 40:03.628
were chatting about their careers.

40:03.667 --> 40:06.033
"Careers" is a euphemism

40:06.070 --> 40:08.470
for what the pilots
were really talking about:

40:08.505 --> 40:12.635
how little they were paid
and how overworked they were.

40:12.676 --> 40:14.769
There would be
no discussion in the media

40:14.812 --> 40:17.076
about why we have
an economic system

40:17.114 --> 40:20.743
that allows a pilot to be paid less
than a manager at Taco Bell.

40:20.784 --> 40:22.183
First Officer Shaw

40:22.219 --> 40:25.848
made between
$16,000 and $20,000 a year

40:25.889 --> 40:29.450
and at one point
worked a second job.

40:29.493 --> 40:31.927
Her 2nd job had been waitressing

40:31.962 --> 40:33.953
at a coffee shop.

40:35.265 --> 40:38.792
How are these companies
able to get away with this?

40:38.836 --> 40:41.532
I guess that's the point of capitalism.

40:41.572 --> 40:44.336
It allows you to get away
with anything,

40:44.375 --> 40:47.745
like making a profit
off the death of an employee.

40:49.313 --> 40:51.679
Sweetie, I can open it.
Let's try it with this.

40:51.715 --> 40:53.774
This is Irma Johnson.

40:53.817 --> 40:56.786
Irma's husband Dan
worked in middle management

40:56.820 --> 40:58.981
at Amegy Bank in Houston, Texas.

40:59.023 --> 41:01.082
- Wanna try to spread it?
- No.

41:01.125 --> 41:03.650
Dan recently died of cancer,

41:03.694 --> 41:07.926
leaving behind Irma
and their 2 sons.

41:07.965 --> 41:10.525
But unbeknownst to Irma,
Amegy had taken out

41:10.567 --> 41:14.526
a secret life insurance policy
on Dan's life.

41:14.571 --> 41:18.803
The bank generously named itself
as the beneficiary

41:18.842 --> 41:21.333
in the event of Dan's death.

41:21.378 --> 41:24.506
The insurance company
then accidentally informed Irma

41:24.548 --> 41:28.678
that Amegy Bank had received
a check for $1½ million

41:28.719 --> 41:31.654
just weeks after Dan died.

41:31.689 --> 41:33.486
Thank you for helping.

41:33.524 --> 41:34.582
They never told me.

41:34.625 --> 41:38.152
I wanted to find out, well,
why did they purchase a policy for him?

41:38.195 --> 41:40.129
- You didn't know about it?
- No.

41:40.164 --> 41:43.827
And they named themselves
as the beneficiary.

41:43.867 --> 41:44.856
Yeah.

41:44.902 --> 41:47.063
So your husband's death

41:47.104 --> 41:50.073
made them $1.5 million richer?

41:52.409 --> 41:55.936
I know it's not right
for them to try to profit

41:55.979 --> 41:58.413
from my husband's death.

41:58.449 --> 42:00.246
When I first realized
what was happening,

42:00.284 --> 42:04.345
I was in disbelief.

42:04.388 --> 42:07.118
- It's hurtful.
- I'm so sorry.

42:12.529 --> 42:16.124
it's hurtful and I wanted answers.

42:16.166 --> 42:18.828
Irma contacted Michael D. Myers,

42:18.869 --> 42:21.360
a local attorney who had
already been looking into

42:21.405 --> 42:24.704
these kind of corporate
insurance policies on their employees.

42:26.110 --> 42:28.704
With the normal use of life insurance,
where you're guarding against

42:28.746 --> 42:33.308
the loss of a loved one
or a breadwinner of the family,

42:33.350 --> 42:37.753
you don't want that person to die.

42:37.788 --> 42:39.949
With these policies,
the companies that buy these

42:39.990 --> 42:41.855
want the employees to die

42:41.892 --> 42:44.588
in accordance
with the policy projections.

42:44.628 --> 42:48.530
You are more valuable dead
to a company than alive.

42:49.833 --> 42:53.325
American Greetings, RR Donnelly & Sons,
and Proctor & Gamble

42:53.370 --> 42:56.134
are all having problems
with mortality.

42:56.173 --> 42:58.664
These 4 combined programs
are running at 50%

42:58.709 --> 43:00.199
of expected mortality.

43:00.244 --> 43:03.702
These clients are acutely aware
of this problem.

43:03.747 --> 43:06.443
Basically here the broker
is complaining

43:06.483 --> 43:08.883
that not enough
employees are dying.

43:08.919 --> 43:12.616
And therefore the investment returns
are not matching the projections.

43:12.656 --> 43:15.090
The broker writes
that NCC is running

43:15.125 --> 43:17.821
at 78% of expected mortality.

43:17.861 --> 43:21.729
Okay, so 78% of the people
we expected to die died.

43:21.765 --> 43:24.996
But the problem with that
is 3 of them were suicides.

43:25.035 --> 43:27.162
And you can't count
on that every year.

43:27.204 --> 43:29.229
Can you think of any other situation

43:29.273 --> 43:33.607
were you'd actually want
people to die?

43:33.644 --> 43:37.842
Combatants in war, I guess.

43:38.681 --> 43:41.681
When do you want people to die?

43:41.718 --> 43:43.345
I-I don't know.

43:43.387 --> 43:47.187
War situations,
terrorism situations.

43:49.126 --> 43:51.822
Drug trials, perhaps.
I don't know.

43:51.862 --> 43:54.456
I don't know.
That's an odd question.

43:54.498 --> 43:57.729
I didn't understand
how any of this could be legal.

43:57.768 --> 44:00.601
After all, there's a reason
that there's a law

44:00.637 --> 44:05.040
prohibiting me from taking out
a fire insurance policy on your house

44:05.075 --> 44:09.307
because I have a vested interest
in your house burning down.

44:09.346 --> 44:12.474
Since Attorney Myers had been
researching this for years,

44:12.516 --> 44:14.575
I asked him which companies
were profiting

44:14.618 --> 44:16.415
from these insurance policies.

44:16.453 --> 44:17.886
I don't know,
you don't know,

44:17.921 --> 44:20.549
because there's no place
you can go and find out

44:20.591 --> 44:24.220
whether your company
is a purchaser

44:24.261 --> 44:26.559
- of these types of products.
- Which ones do you know?

44:26.597 --> 44:28.292
The ones that we know
that have slipped out are

44:28.332 --> 44:30.357
Bank of America, Citibank,

44:30.400 --> 44:33.699
Wal-Mart, Winn-Dixie,
Proctor & Gamble,

44:33.737 --> 44:35.864
McDonnell Douglas, Hershey,

44:35.906 --> 44:38.875
Nestlé, AT&T
Southwestern Bell,

44:38.909 --> 44:40.968
Ameritech, American Express--

44:41.011 --> 44:43.070
- This is blue chip you're talking about.
- Yeah.

44:43.113 --> 44:46.310
These aren't fly-by-night companies
trying to do a scam here

44:46.350 --> 44:48.511
so they can collect a check
if one of their employees dies.

44:48.552 --> 44:51.851
There are probably
several million Americans

44:51.889 --> 44:55.723
who are covered by one of these policies
or have been at some point.

44:55.759 --> 44:57.021
There's a lot of it out there.

44:57.060 --> 44:59.221
This is Paul Smith.

44:59.263 --> 45:02.824
He used to be what is known
as a loyal employee.

45:02.866 --> 45:07.098
I worked for Wal-Mart for 18 years
and I gave them 110%.

45:07.137 --> 45:08.900
I mean, I loved that company.

45:08.939 --> 45:10.429
And as it turned out,
Wal-Mart took out

45:10.474 --> 45:13.534
over 350,000
life insurance policies

45:13.577 --> 45:15.704
on rank and file associates.

45:15.746 --> 45:16.940
These weren't executives.

45:16.980 --> 45:20.416
These were people like my wife,
a cake decorator for 18 months.

45:20.450 --> 45:24.045
That's the type of people they were taking
insurance policies out on.

45:24.087 --> 45:28.080
Paul's wife LaDonna left her job
at the Wal-Mart bakery

45:28.125 --> 45:30.923
so she could be a stay-at-home mom
for her 2 kids.

45:30.961 --> 45:34.124
She had asthma real real bad.

45:34.164 --> 45:36.098
She went into
the emergency room one night

45:36.133 --> 45:38.101
and a nurse comes out and says,
"Are you Mr. Smith?"

45:38.135 --> 45:39.625
And I said, "Yes."

45:39.670 --> 45:43.731
And she said, "We don't think
your wife's gonna make it."

45:43.774 --> 45:45.742
LaDonna slipped into a coma

45:45.776 --> 45:48.108
from which she would
never awaken.

45:48.145 --> 45:50.306
Her family rushed to the hospital,

45:50.347 --> 45:52.781
even though there was nothing
they could do to help.

45:52.816 --> 45:55.376
There was a wall here
and LaDonna's in the room

45:55.419 --> 45:56.852
on the other side of the wall.

45:56.887 --> 45:59.151
And Jessica kept saying,
"Where is she?"

45:59.189 --> 46:01.817
And I said, "She's right on
the other side of that wall."

46:01.858 --> 46:05.453
And Jessica said,
"Can we cut a hole in the wall

46:05.495 --> 46:07.986
so that we can see her?"

46:08.031 --> 46:10.056
And that just sticks with me.

46:10.100 --> 46:11.931
Do you remember that?

46:14.037 --> 46:18.406
We had to stay in there with her,
and so we'd write letters to her.

46:18.442 --> 46:22.902
"My dear wife, I miss you more
than any words can possibly say.

46:22.946 --> 46:24.504
You are my life.

46:24.548 --> 46:26.948
You always see beauty
in the simplest things.

46:26.984 --> 46:31.421
I've always admired you for that.
I wish I could have told you that more.

46:31.455 --> 46:33.719
I want you to come back
to me soon.

46:33.757 --> 46:36.749
I still have a lot left to learn
from you, baby doll.

46:36.793 --> 46:38.954
Your loving husband, Paul."

46:40.897 --> 46:43.331
You okay, Wesley?

46:44.735 --> 46:47.499
She was 26 years old.

46:47.537 --> 46:50.472
You're silly.

46:50.507 --> 46:54.170
The younger a person is,
the higher the benefit is

46:54.211 --> 46:57.009
because they're expected
to live longer.

46:57.047 --> 46:59.242
Women are also expected
to live longer than men.

46:59.282 --> 47:02.251
So the most valuable employee
to the company

47:02.285 --> 47:05.186
if they're dead,
is a young woman.

47:05.222 --> 47:06.814
LaDonna's death earned

47:06.857 --> 47:09.087
one of the richest corporations
in the world

47:09.126 --> 47:11.686
an extra $81,000.

47:11.728 --> 47:15.061
I was faced with over $100,000
worth of medical bills

47:15.098 --> 47:18.431
and a $6,000 funeral

47:18.468 --> 47:21.926
and Wal-Mart didn't offer a penny
to help with that.

47:21.972 --> 47:25.237
I did trust them.

47:25.275 --> 47:28.540
And never in a million years
would I have ever thought

47:28.578 --> 47:31.513
that somewhere
on a profit statement,

47:31.548 --> 47:34.540
"Dead associate, $81,000."

47:34.584 --> 47:38.577
Wal-Mart doesn't care about you.

47:38.622 --> 47:40.453
When someone passes away,

47:40.490 --> 47:43.288
they shouldn't get
something out of it.

47:53.970 --> 47:56.461
The common denominator
to each form of coverage

47:56.506 --> 47:58.531
is that when the employee dies,

47:58.575 --> 48:01.806
the employer gets paid
the insurance benefits.

48:01.845 --> 48:05.008
They're often referred to
as "dead peasant insurance."

48:05.048 --> 48:08.609
Dead peasants?
Why'd they use such a creepy name?

48:08.652 --> 48:11.780
It's very creepy.
I don't know what it means either.

48:11.822 --> 48:12.982
Dead is clear.

48:13.023 --> 48:15.753
That's the worker who's passed away,
so they're dead.

48:15.792 --> 48:18.226
Peasant, I don't know why
they chose that word.

48:18.261 --> 48:20.286
I don't know if it has
some historical significance

48:20.330 --> 48:23.322
or that's just the way they view
the relative value

48:23.366 --> 48:25.095
of the employees' lives.

48:25.135 --> 48:26.727
Dead peasants?

48:26.770 --> 48:28.897
Yeah, amongst themselves
that's what they call it.

48:30.474 --> 48:34.706
It's insulting to refer
to my husband like that.

48:41.852 --> 48:43.410
It turned out that Amegy Bank

48:43.453 --> 48:46.149
had a second
dead peasant policy on Dan,

48:46.189 --> 48:50.182
bringing their total take
to nearly $5 million.

48:53.029 --> 48:55.930
- Is capitalism a sin?
- Yes.

48:55.999 --> 48:58.559
Capitalism for me and for many of us

48:58.602 --> 49:01.935
at this present moment is an evil.

49:01.972 --> 49:05.738
It's contrary to all that's good.
It's contrary to the common good.

49:05.775 --> 49:08.005
It's contrary to compassion.

49:08.044 --> 49:11.013
It's contrary to
all of the major religions.

49:11.047 --> 49:15.108
Capitalism is precisely
what the holy books,

49:15.152 --> 49:19.816
our holy books in particular,
remind us is unjust

49:19.856 --> 49:22.825
and in some form and fashion,

49:22.859 --> 49:27.626
God will come down
and eradicate somehow.

49:27.664 --> 49:29.996
This was Father Dick Preston,

49:30.033 --> 49:33.366
the priest from Flint
who married my wife and me.

49:33.403 --> 49:35.564
Capitalism is wrong,

49:35.605 --> 49:39.336
and therefore
has to be eliminated.

49:39.376 --> 49:41.367
Eliminated?

49:41.411 --> 49:43.402
That might be a little harsh,

49:43.446 --> 49:45.437
so I decided to go
and talk to the priest

49:45.482 --> 49:47.780
that married my sister
and brother-in-law.

49:47.817 --> 49:50.115
I'm sure he would have
a more balanced approach

49:50.153 --> 49:52.280
when it came to capitalism.

49:52.322 --> 49:56.258
It is immoral, it is obscene,
it is outrageous.

49:56.293 --> 49:59.023
You know...

49:59.062 --> 50:01.394
it is really radical evil.

50:01.431 --> 50:03.729
It's radically evil.

50:04.267 --> 50:07.294
Does their boss know
that they're talking like this?

50:07.337 --> 50:10.363
I thought it best to go
and check this out with the bishop.

50:10.407 --> 50:12.671
Bishop Thomas Gumbleton:
The system doesn't seem to be

50:12.709 --> 50:16.475
providing for the well being
of all the people.

50:16.513 --> 50:19.414
And that's what makes it

50:19.449 --> 50:21.917
almost in its very nature

50:21.952 --> 50:25.888
something contrary
to Jesus who said,

50:25.922 --> 50:29.449
"Blessed are the poor,
woe to the rich."

50:29.492 --> 50:32.689
That's right out
of St. Luke's gospel.

50:32.729 --> 50:35.027
How have we put up
with this system for so long?

50:35.065 --> 50:37.226
I mean, it's--
they talk about--

50:37.267 --> 50:41.636
The system has built into it
what we call propaganda.

50:41.671 --> 50:43.901
I'm in awe of propaganda--

50:43.940 --> 50:46.909
the ability to convince people

50:46.943 --> 50:49.878
who are victimized
by this very system

50:49.913 --> 50:52.882
to support the system
and see it as good.

50:52.916 --> 50:56.317
We know that American capitalism
is morally right

50:56.353 --> 50:58.514
because its chief elements--

50:58.555 --> 51:01.615
private ownership,
the profit motive

51:01.658 --> 51:04.684
and the competitive market--
are wholesome and good.

51:04.728 --> 51:08.027
They are compatible with God's laws
and the teachings of the Bible.

51:09.032 --> 51:10.932
For as long as I can remember,

51:10.967 --> 51:14.562
I've been told that competition
and profit are good things.

51:14.604 --> 51:16.697
They are compatible with God's laws

51:16.740 --> 51:17.900
and the teachings of the Bible.

51:17.941 --> 51:21.274
And if increasing profits
means locking up a few kids

51:21.311 --> 51:23.438
or cashing in on the death
of an employee...

51:23.480 --> 51:26.313
Compatible with God's laws
and the teachings of the Bible.

51:26.349 --> 51:29.614
it is morally right to provide
for the stockholders.

51:29.653 --> 51:31.985
They are compatible with God's laws

51:32.022 --> 51:33.250
and the teachings of the Bible.

51:33.290 --> 51:36.521
Debt, eviction and exploitation.

51:36.559 --> 51:40.017
God's laws and the teachings of the Bible.

51:40.063 --> 51:42.998
What were we really
pledging our allegiance to?

51:43.033 --> 51:45.968
The profit motive.

51:46.002 --> 51:48.698
And so all good Americans
came to act as if they believed

51:48.738 --> 51:51.901
our capitalist economic system
was compatible

51:51.941 --> 51:54.273
with the teachings of the Bible.

52:02.552 --> 52:06.386
When I was a kid,
I wanted to be a priest.

52:06.423 --> 52:08.220
It wasn't because
of the fancy getups

52:08.258 --> 52:10.522
or the Knights of Columbus
escorts,

52:10.560 --> 52:13.859
or even the groovy nuns
who were so good to me.

52:14.898 --> 52:18.425
It was because of the priests
who went on the march from Selma,

52:18.468 --> 52:21.028
or tried to stop the war,

52:21.071 --> 52:24.529
or devoted their lives to the poor.

52:24.574 --> 52:28.533
They told me quite clearly
what Jesus said,

52:28.578 --> 52:32.947
that the first shall be last
and the last shall be first;

52:32.982 --> 52:35.678
That the rich man
will have a very hard time

52:35.719 --> 52:37.778
getting into heaven;

52:37.821 --> 52:41.655
That we will be judged by how
we treat the least among us;

52:41.691 --> 52:44.319
And that there are no people
more important to God

52:44.361 --> 52:46.886
than the poor.

52:46.930 --> 52:49.455
Since that time,
it seems that Jesus got hijacked

52:49.499 --> 52:52.468
by a lot of people who believe
that the son of God

52:52.502 --> 52:56.871
was sent here to create
heaven on earth for the well-to-do.

52:56.906 --> 52:59.101
I must have missed
that part of the Bible

52:59.142 --> 53:02.441
where Jesus became a capitalist.

53:06.750 --> 53:08.342
Please tell me, master,

53:08.385 --> 53:11.149
what must I do
to have eternal life?

53:11.187 --> 53:14.714
Go forth and maximize profits.

53:16.559 --> 53:19.892
You say the Kingdom of Heaven
is at hand,

53:19.929 --> 53:21.453
but when exactly will it come?

53:21.498 --> 53:25.696
When you deregulate
the banking industry.

53:25.735 --> 53:28.829
Help me.

53:28.872 --> 53:31.397
I've been this way for 20 years.

53:33.243 --> 53:36.735
I'm sorry, I cannot heal
your pre-existing condition.

53:38.748 --> 53:40.409
He'll have to pay out of pocket.

53:43.820 --> 53:46.311
Somehow, I don't think
Jesus came to earth

53:46.356 --> 53:49.519
so he could ring the bell
at the New York Stock Exchange.

53:49.559 --> 53:51.550
And yet,
from the very beginning,

53:51.594 --> 53:54.427
the rich have claimed him
for their own.

53:54.464 --> 53:58.264
When I'm on Wall Street
and I realize

53:58.301 --> 54:02.431
that that's the very nerve center
of American capitalism,

54:02.472 --> 54:06.135
and I realize
what capitalism has done

54:06.176 --> 54:09.805
for working people in America,
to me that's a holy place.

54:09.846 --> 54:11.006
Let me add to it.

54:11.047 --> 54:15.074
Over the whole duration of the Iraq war
and the terror war,

54:15.118 --> 54:18.952
you look at the world's stock markets
and you look at the world economy,

54:18.988 --> 54:22.947
and despite these horrible pockets
of unrest and killing and murdering

54:22.992 --> 54:25.893
that we've been describing,
it's never been better.

54:25.929 --> 54:27.863
The global economy
has never been better

54:27.897 --> 54:30.525
and the global stock markets
have never been better, Jimmy.

54:30.567 --> 54:32.592
It is either a God-given miracle

54:32.635 --> 54:34.603
or it has something to do
with the victories

54:34.637 --> 54:37.003
of the spreading world
of capitalism or both.

54:37.040 --> 54:38.974
They think
Wall Street's a holy place.

54:39.008 --> 54:41.943
What do you think
Jesus would think of capitalism?

54:41.978 --> 54:46.347
I think he would
simply refuse to--

54:46.382 --> 54:49.619
to be part of it.

54:50.787 --> 54:53.654
Jesus would refuse
to be part of it,

54:53.690 --> 54:55.658
but he probably had
a special place up there

54:55.692 --> 54:58.627
for whoever leaked
a secret Citibank memo

54:58.661 --> 55:02.028
about their plan to rule the world.

55:02.065 --> 55:04.056
Back in 2005 and 2006,

55:04.100 --> 55:06.432
Citigroup wrote
3 confidential memos

55:06.469 --> 55:10.929
to their wealthiest investors
about how things were going.

55:10.974 --> 55:13.374
They reached the conclusion
that the United States

55:13.409 --> 55:15.639
was no longer
really a democracy,

55:15.678 --> 55:18.442
but had become a plutonomy--

55:18.481 --> 55:21.575
a society controlled exclusively
by and for the benefit

55:21.618 --> 55:24.712
of the top 1 %
of the population

55:24.754 --> 55:26.847
who now had
more financial wealth

55:26.890 --> 55:30.519
than the bottom 95% combined.

55:30.560 --> 55:33.791
The memo gloated about the growing gap
between rich and poor

55:33.830 --> 55:37.288
and how they were now
the new aristocracy

55:37.333 --> 55:41.269
and that there was no end in sight
for the gravy train they were on.

55:41.304 --> 55:44.865
There was, though,
one problem.

55:44.908 --> 55:46.432
According to Citigroup,

55:46.476 --> 55:49.070
the most potent
and short-term threat

55:49.112 --> 55:50.909
would be societies demanding

55:50.947 --> 55:53.541
a more equitable share
of the wealth.

55:53.583 --> 55:57.952
In other words,
the peasants might revolt.

55:57.987 --> 56:00.353
Citigroup lamented
that the non-rich

56:00.390 --> 56:02.858
might not have
much economic power,

56:02.892 --> 56:06.419
but they do have
equal voting power with the rich.

56:06.462 --> 56:09.431
One person, one vote.

56:09.465 --> 56:12.127
And that's what
really scares them--

56:12.168 --> 56:14.602
that we can still vote.

56:14.637 --> 56:17.936
In fact, we have
99% of the votes

56:17.974 --> 56:20.772
and they only have 1%.

56:23.846 --> 56:27.805
So why do the 99%
put up with this?

56:27.850 --> 56:31.286
According to Citigroup,
it's because the majority of the electorate

56:31.321 --> 56:33.812
believe that someday
they will have a chance

56:33.856 --> 56:36.381
of becoming
well-to-do themselves

56:36.426 --> 56:39.589
if they just keep trying
hard enough.

56:41.931 --> 56:44.229
The wealthy were pleased
that so many people

56:44.267 --> 56:47.100
had bought in
to the American Dream

56:47.136 --> 56:50.196
while they, the rich,
had no intention

56:50.239 --> 56:53.140
of ever sharing it with anyone.

56:53.176 --> 56:56.475
I think capitalism is a lot more
important than democracy.

56:56.512 --> 56:58.878
I'm not even a big believer
in democracy.

56:58.915 --> 57:02.510
I always say that democracy is--
can be 2 wolves and a sheep

57:02.552 --> 57:04.213
deciding on what to have
for dinner.

57:04.253 --> 57:07.484
This is Stephen Moore--
no relation--

57:07.523 --> 57:09.957
a columnist
and an editorial board member

57:09.993 --> 57:11.756
of "The Wall Street Journal,"

57:11.794 --> 57:15.230
the daily bible
of corporate America.

57:15.264 --> 57:18.324
Look, I'm in favor of people
having the right to vote

57:18.368 --> 57:20.836
and things like that, but you know
there are a lot of countries

57:20.870 --> 57:24.738
that have the right to vote
that are still poor.

57:24.774 --> 57:28.141
Democracy doesn't always lead
to a good economy

57:28.177 --> 57:30.111
or even a good political system.

57:30.146 --> 57:33.513
With capitalism, you are free
to do what you want,

57:33.549 --> 57:35.608
to make whatever you want
out of yourself.

57:35.652 --> 57:37.176
It doesn't mean
you're gonna succeed.

57:37.220 --> 57:41.623
Remember, the US Constitution
does not guarantee happiness.

57:42.258 --> 57:44.286
The Constitution.

57:44.327 --> 57:48.093
All my life I've heard that America
is a capitalist country.

57:48.131 --> 57:52.397
So I went to see the original Constitution
and check out if it was true.

57:52.435 --> 57:55.871
I'm trying to see where it sets up
our economic system,

57:55.905 --> 57:59.136
like where it says we have
a capitalist economy.

57:59.175 --> 58:01.336
The jurisdiction.

58:01.377 --> 58:03.174
- Judicial part of the--
- Down there?

58:03.212 --> 58:07.012
There was no mention
of free market or free enterprise

58:07.050 --> 58:09.644
or capitalism anywhere.

58:10.687 --> 58:13.952
In fact, all I saw was
"We the people,"

58:13.990 --> 58:16.584
something about
"a more perfect union,"

58:16.626 --> 58:19.993
and "promoting
the general welfare."

58:20.029 --> 58:24.523
Welfare, union, we?

58:24.567 --> 58:26.967
That sounded like that other -ism.

58:27.003 --> 58:30.439
But no, that's democracy.

58:30.473 --> 58:33.175
And I began to wonder,
"What would it be like

58:33.242 --> 58:36.575
if the workplace
was a democracy?"

58:36.612 --> 58:39.945
There's always been a big separation
between how the country is run

58:39.982 --> 58:43.213
and how businesses
are supposed to run.

58:43.252 --> 58:44.446
It's true.

58:44.487 --> 58:46.352
There seems to be a disconnect

58:46.389 --> 58:48.721
between our professed love
of democracy

58:48.758 --> 58:51.784
and how we're so willing
to accept a dictatorship

58:51.828 --> 58:54.695
every day we show up to work.

58:54.731 --> 58:58.531
It's not that way
at Isthmus Engineering in Wisconsin.

58:58.568 --> 59:02.402
They design and build
robotic machines for industry.

59:02.438 --> 59:05.601
It's a $15 million-a-year business.

59:05.641 --> 59:07.438
All of the workers

59:07.477 --> 59:10.810
are the owners of the business.

59:10.847 --> 59:14.408
He's not talking about
some bullshit stock option.

59:14.450 --> 59:17.851
He means they're the true owners.

59:17.887 --> 59:20.720
And it's a democratically-run
operation where every member

59:20.757 --> 59:23.726
has one vote and an equal say.

59:23.760 --> 59:26.024
- All in favor?
- All in favor?

59:26.062 --> 59:29.088
It takes the money
out of the equation.

59:29.132 --> 59:31.157
By taking the money
out of the equation

59:31.200 --> 59:33.430
so that they can call the shots,

59:33.469 --> 59:35.801
they end up making more money.

59:35.838 --> 59:37.466
Cool?

59:42.145 --> 59:44.943
And how patriotic
that they want to extend

59:44.981 --> 59:48.815
their love of American democracy
to their job.

59:55.124 --> 59:57.058
Just imagine if the place
where you worked

59:57.093 --> 01:00:00.256
was run by you
and your fellow workers.

01:00:00.296 --> 01:00:02.161
You probably wouldn't
lay off your coworkers

01:00:02.198 --> 01:00:05.133
to increase the value
of your stock, would you?

01:00:05.168 --> 01:00:06.635
Or give yourself
a pay raise

01:00:06.669 --> 01:00:09.536
while making your coworkers
take a pay cut.

01:00:09.572 --> 01:00:11.437
We don't really do that here.

01:00:11.474 --> 01:00:15.069
You really can't because everyone else
would be looking at you

01:00:15.111 --> 01:00:17.671
saying, "Why is this guy
so fricking greedy?"

01:00:17.713 --> 01:00:20.307
You know,
it would be too obvious.

01:00:20.349 --> 01:00:22.214
The bottom line is you've
got plenty of people

01:00:22.251 --> 01:00:24.048
who roll up their sleeves
every day and go to work.

01:00:24.086 --> 01:00:25.986
But if there's someone
way up there on the chain

01:00:26.022 --> 01:00:29.048
that collects all the extra money,
that's not fair.

01:00:30.291 --> 01:00:32.857
Fairness in the workplace--

01:00:32.895 --> 01:00:35.227
what a novel idea.

01:00:36.666 --> 01:00:39.897
Out in California,
there's a bread factory

01:00:39.936 --> 01:00:43.497
where workers make thousands
of loaves of bread every day

01:00:43.539 --> 01:00:45.530
The more hours you work towards

01:00:45.575 --> 01:00:46.872
the benefit
of the co-op,

01:00:46.909 --> 01:00:49.776
the more you share
in the profits.

01:00:49.812 --> 01:00:52.007
The workers are happy here.

01:00:52.048 --> 01:00:54.516
No big Is, little yous.
Everyone's the same.

01:00:54.550 --> 01:00:58.042
Me as the CEO,
I get the same share

01:00:58.087 --> 01:01:00.112
that anybody else does.

01:01:00.156 --> 01:01:01.953
And that has proven

01:01:01.991 --> 01:01:04.323
to be very lucrative
for us as workers.

01:01:06.162 --> 01:01:10.724
Assembly-line workers here
earn over $65,000 a year,

01:01:10.766 --> 01:01:12.859
more than 3 times the pay

01:01:12.902 --> 01:01:15.462
for a starting pilot
at American Eagle.

01:01:15.504 --> 01:01:18.302
I'm just hoping
that people take notice

01:01:18.341 --> 01:01:20.502
of this type
of organizational activity

01:01:20.543 --> 01:01:23.944
and start considering it
as an alternative.

01:01:23.980 --> 01:01:25.311
Why do you want
to get rich?

01:01:25.348 --> 01:01:27.282
How many cars do
you really need in life?

01:01:27.316 --> 01:01:31.912
Clearly, he's not a car guy,
but that's okay.

01:01:31.954 --> 01:01:35.481
His bread factory and hundreds of other
worker-owned businesses

01:01:35.524 --> 01:01:39.119
are proof that people aren't always
motivated by profit.

01:01:41.998 --> 01:01:44.626
An historic victory over a dread disease.

01:01:44.667 --> 01:01:48.034
Instead of using his genius
to make a ton of money,

01:01:48.070 --> 01:01:51.335
Dr. Jonas Salk spent
all of his time

01:01:51.374 --> 01:01:53.865
putting monkey kidneys
in a blender

01:01:53.910 --> 01:01:55.969
trying to find a cure
for polio.

01:01:56.012 --> 01:02:00.881
And when he did,
he decided to give it away for free.

01:02:00.917 --> 01:02:03.977
This man could have been rich
many times over

01:02:04.020 --> 01:02:07.353
had he sold his vaccine
to a pharmaceutical company.

01:02:07.390 --> 01:02:09.824
But he thought
his talents should be used

01:02:09.859 --> 01:02:11.053
for the greater good.

01:02:11.093 --> 01:02:14.028
And the decent salary
he made as a doctor

01:02:14.063 --> 01:02:16.463
and a research professor
was enough for him to live

01:02:16.499 --> 01:02:18.558
a comfortable life.

01:02:18.601 --> 01:02:21.001
Who owns the patent
on this vaccine?

01:02:21.037 --> 01:02:23.005
Well, the people,
I would say.

01:02:23.039 --> 01:02:26.600
There is no patent.
Would you patent the sun?

01:02:26.642 --> 01:02:30.476
Yes, we've come a long way
since the days of Dr. Salk.

01:02:30.513 --> 01:02:34.643
Because today our best minds
are used for something else.

01:02:35.084 --> 01:02:38.801
Where do we send our top
math and science people?

01:02:39.054 --> 01:02:40.085
Into finance.

01:02:40.122 --> 01:02:42.590
They don't go into
science in America.

01:02:42.625 --> 01:02:45.321
They go to Wall Street.

01:02:45.361 --> 01:02:48.421
Today's students,
unlike in Dr. Salk's time,

01:02:48.464 --> 01:02:51.024
can graduate from college
with a student loan debt

01:02:51.067 --> 01:02:54.093
of up to $100,000 or more.

01:02:54.136 --> 01:02:56.434
These students are then
beholden to the banks

01:02:56.472 --> 01:02:59.441
for the next 20 years.

01:02:59.475 --> 01:03:02.308
And the best way for them
to pay off these banks

01:03:02.345 --> 01:03:04.279
is to go to work for them

01:03:04.313 --> 01:03:06.941
instead of working
for the common good.

01:03:06.983 --> 01:03:11.352
We've taken people that could
be enormously productive--

01:03:11.387 --> 01:03:13.014
just what we're short of
in America--

01:03:13.055 --> 01:03:16.081
and we take them and we
put them in an activity

01:03:16.125 --> 01:03:18.116
that isn't simply less
productive,

01:03:18.160 --> 01:03:20.958
but where they're
actually destructive;

01:03:20.997 --> 01:03:24.797
where actually every day they work,
they make the world worse.

01:03:24.834 --> 01:03:27.894
So what exactly were the top
students from Harvard

01:03:27.937 --> 01:03:29.928
and other schools
working on these days?

01:03:29.972 --> 01:03:31.997
Derivatives... derivatives...
derivatives... derivatives...

01:03:32.041 --> 01:03:34.441
Credit default swaps.

01:03:34.477 --> 01:03:36.502
I can't make any sense
out of this.

01:03:36.545 --> 01:03:38.308
I might as well quit.

01:03:38.397 --> 01:03:40.097
That's exactly how I felt

01:03:40.190 --> 01:03:42.351
when I started hearing
these new terms.

01:03:42.393 --> 01:03:46.523
So I went down to the New York Stock
Exchange to get some answers.

01:03:46.563 --> 01:03:48.292
Sir, can you explain
derivatives to me?

01:03:48.332 --> 01:03:50.562
Can anybody explain
derivatives or credit default swaps?

01:03:50.601 --> 01:03:51.829
Can someone explain
to me what these are?

01:03:51.869 --> 01:03:54.099
Sir, can you tell me what
a credit default swap is?

01:03:54.138 --> 01:03:55.662
Can you explain
a derivative to me?

01:03:55.706 --> 01:03:57.173
Can you tell me
what a derivative is?

01:03:57.207 --> 01:03:59.471
- Nobody'll talk to me.
- I'm just a blue-collar guy.

01:03:59.510 --> 01:04:01.171
I can see that.
Hey.

01:04:01.211 --> 01:04:03.736
- I'm looking for some advice.
- Yeah, good.

01:04:03.781 --> 01:04:06.909
You guys got any
advice for me here?

01:04:06.951 --> 01:04:08.942
A derivative?
Credit default swap?

01:04:10.487 --> 01:04:13.012
I did find one guy on Wall Street

01:04:13.057 --> 01:04:14.888
who wasn't a film critic.

01:04:14.925 --> 01:04:18.292
Marcus Haupt is an Ivy League
educated engineer

01:04:18.329 --> 01:04:20.957
who was a vice president
of Lehman Brothers

01:04:20.998 --> 01:04:23.489
and spent 15 years
on Wall Street

01:04:23.534 --> 01:04:26.560
creating what they call
complex financial instruments.

01:04:26.603 --> 01:04:28.093
What is a derivative?

01:04:28.138 --> 01:04:30.231
A derivative
is a secondary bet

01:04:30.274 --> 01:04:32.071
