the American people
in unprecedented numbers

01:30:37.907 --> 01:30:40.933
flooded Capitol Hill
with millions of messages

01:30:40.976 --> 01:30:43.672
demanding that
Congress vote no.

01:30:47.149 --> 01:30:50.050
The bailout package
was defeated today,

01:30:50.085 --> 01:30:52.315
voted down in the House
of Representatives.

01:30:52.354 --> 01:30:54.049
The stock market plunged--

01:30:54.089 --> 01:30:56.751
plunged to the single
greatest point loss

01:30:56.792 --> 01:30:59.090
in the Dow average
in one day ever.

01:30:59.128 --> 01:31:00.720
The question is this:

01:31:00.763 --> 01:31:03.129
is the failure of
the bailout reason enough

01:31:03.165 --> 01:31:06.362
to vote all the incumbents
out of office in 5 weeks?

01:31:06.402 --> 01:31:08.267
12 votes killed it.

01:31:08.304 --> 01:31:10.499
So did the voices of a lot
of the American people

01:31:10.539 --> 01:31:13.872
who called their representatives
and said no.

01:31:13.909 --> 01:31:16.275
Then Congress voted no.

01:31:16.312 --> 01:31:18.280
Tonight Congress
has left town.

01:31:18.314 --> 01:31:21.181
It was a rebuke that Congress
and Wall Street

01:31:21.216 --> 01:31:24.014
had rarely,
if ever, experienced.

01:31:24.053 --> 01:31:27.147
It was what the Citibank
memo had warned against:

01:31:27.189 --> 01:31:28.952
That if the peasants
ever chose

01:31:28.991 --> 01:31:31.118
to exercise their
democratic rights,

01:31:31.160 --> 01:31:34.152
the pillaging by the wealthy
would be over.

01:31:34.196 --> 01:31:38.326
So Paulson and company headed
back up to Capitol Hill.

01:31:38.367 --> 01:31:41.666
And faster than you can say
"Check, please,"

01:31:41.704 --> 01:31:45.470
they cut a backroom deal
with the help of the Democrats.

01:31:47.209 --> 01:31:48.699
This issue supersedes
an election.

01:31:48.744 --> 01:31:50.644
We need to get this right.
We need to do it quickly.

01:31:50.679 --> 01:31:52.112
I agree with the secretary.

01:31:52.147 --> 01:31:54.581
It's not gonna openly cost
all these hundreds of billions.

01:31:54.617 --> 01:31:56.585
We will recover most of it,
maybe all of it.

01:31:56.619 --> 01:31:59.713
The Democrats became

01:31:59.755 --> 01:32:03.282
the delivery man
for a bill

01:32:03.325 --> 01:32:05.657
for the Republican
president.

01:32:05.694 --> 01:32:09.186
The presidents and presidents-
to-be made phone calls

01:32:09.231 --> 01:32:12.359
and members-- I know
at least 2 members

01:32:12.401 --> 01:32:14.801
who have an interest
in the US Senate,

01:32:14.837 --> 01:32:16.031
and promises were made.

01:32:17.439 --> 01:32:19.634
Within days, the Congress

01:32:19.675 --> 01:32:21.666
did an amazing about-face

01:32:21.710 --> 01:32:25.771
and gave the banks the 700-plus
billion they wanted,

01:32:25.814 --> 01:32:27.679
the people be damned.

01:32:27.716 --> 01:32:30.651
On this vote
the yeas are 263,

01:32:30.686 --> 01:32:33.985
the nays are 171.
The motion is adopted.

01:32:34.023 --> 01:32:38.357
It was very carefully planned
to happen when it did,

01:32:38.394 --> 01:32:42.421
to involve the players
that it did.

01:32:42.464 --> 01:32:46.457
The message was carefully handled.

01:32:46.502 --> 01:32:48.527
They had Congress right where
they wanted them.

01:32:48.570 --> 01:32:51.698
You don't think it
was just happenstance?

01:32:51.740 --> 01:32:53.571
No.

01:32:53.609 --> 01:32:57.170
This was almost like
an intelligence operation

01:32:57.212 --> 01:33:00.579
that had to be coordinated
at the highest levels.

01:33:00.616 --> 01:33:03.176
This whole fiasco shows you

01:33:03.218 --> 01:33:07.917
that there are some forces--

01:33:07.956 --> 01:33:10.550
That are not democratic.

01:33:10.592 --> 01:33:12.457
Right. That are in control.

01:33:12.494 --> 01:33:15.258
Big time.

01:33:15.297 --> 01:33:18.357
They did a masterful job.
Very well executed.

01:33:21.070 --> 01:33:22.298
Do you think it's too harsh

01:33:22.337 --> 01:33:25.738
to call what has happened
here a coup d'état?

01:33:25.774 --> 01:33:27.332
A financial coup d'état?

01:33:27.376 --> 01:33:30.504
No, because I think
that's what's happened.

01:33:30.546 --> 01:33:33.811
- A financial coup d'état?
- Yeah.

01:33:35.584 --> 01:33:37.176
I could agree with that.

01:33:38.520 --> 01:33:40.613
I could agree with that
because the people here

01:33:40.656 --> 01:33:42.590
really aren't in charge.

01:33:42.624 --> 01:33:45.115
Wall Street is in charge.

01:33:46.895 --> 01:33:48.920
Where's our money?

01:33:48.964 --> 01:33:51.364
I don't know.

01:33:51.400 --> 01:33:53.732
Citigroup is spending $50 million

01:33:53.769 --> 01:33:55.396
on a luxury corporate jet.

01:33:55.437 --> 01:33:57.997
You don't know?
But you're the person--

01:33:58.040 --> 01:34:01.032
you're in charge of--
they put you in charge to find out.

01:34:01.076 --> 01:34:02.771
Goldman Sachs has set aside

01:34:02.811 --> 01:34:05.177
6.8 billion for bonuses.

01:34:05.214 --> 01:34:08.547
But Treasury followed
a don't-ask-don't-tell policy.

01:34:08.584 --> 01:34:10.814
They didn't ask the banks

01:34:10.853 --> 01:34:13.083
what they were going to do
with the money.

01:34:13.122 --> 01:34:16.717
And not having asked them,
the banks are not required to tell.

01:34:16.759 --> 01:34:19.421
AIG poolside meetings
at a Valley resort...

01:34:19.461 --> 01:34:20.655
Doesn't make any sense.

01:34:20.696 --> 01:34:23.392
We're getting word
that 73 people

01:34:23.432 --> 01:34:26.367
received at least
$1 million apiece.

01:34:26.401 --> 01:34:28.528
Why would the Department
of Treasury

01:34:28.570 --> 01:34:30.731
not require the banks
to tell them

01:34:30.773 --> 01:34:32.365
what they're doing
with our money?

01:34:32.407 --> 01:34:36.104
You're going to have
to ask Secretary Paulson that question.

01:34:36.145 --> 01:34:38.978
Because I've asked
that question

01:34:39.014 --> 01:34:42.245
in my role as head of the Congressional
Oversight Panel,

01:34:42.284 --> 01:34:44.377
and so far I haven't gotten an answer.
Maybe you'll get a better one.

01:34:46.655 --> 01:34:48.623
Good afternoon.
Hank Paulson's office.

01:34:48.657 --> 01:34:50.181
Yeah, this is Michael Moore.

01:34:50.225 --> 01:34:51.954
I'd like to talk
to Mr. Paulson.

01:34:51.994 --> 01:34:54.053
- I'm sorry. Your name again?
- Michael Moore.

01:34:54.096 --> 01:34:55.654
- Michael Moore?
- Yup.

01:34:56.197 --> 01:34:58.894
Hello? Hello?

01:34:58.934 --> 01:35:01.732
This is crazy what they're doing
with our money.

01:35:01.770 --> 01:35:04.534
If I could get them
to actually give the money back--

01:35:04.573 --> 01:35:06.308
I'd be in favor of that.

01:35:24.193 --> 01:35:26.627
We're here to get the money
back for the American people.

01:35:26.662 --> 01:35:28.493
I understand, sir,
but you can't come in.

01:35:28.530 --> 01:35:29.963
- Can you just take the bag?
- No.

01:35:29.998 --> 01:35:31.556
- Take it up there?
- Absolutely not.

01:35:31.600 --> 01:35:33.534
Fill it up.
I got more bags.

01:35:33.569 --> 01:35:35.366
10 billion probably
won't fit in here.

01:35:35.404 --> 01:35:36.564
You can't help me
get the money?

01:35:36.605 --> 01:35:37.765
I can't help you
get the money.

01:35:37.806 --> 01:35:40.001
What would happen if I made
a run for it right now?

01:35:42.144 --> 01:35:44.704
So I went to another bank.

01:35:45.914 --> 01:35:46.972
We want our money back.

01:35:47.015 --> 01:35:48.573
I went to all the banks.

01:35:48.617 --> 01:35:50.881
- You've seen this guy?
- Yeah.

01:35:50.919 --> 01:35:53.251
Okay, we're here to make
a citizen's arrest, actually.

01:35:53.288 --> 01:35:55.688
Just drop it
from the windows.

01:35:55.724 --> 01:35:58.284
And everywhere I went...

01:36:00.028 --> 01:36:01.325
I got the same reaction.

01:36:01.363 --> 01:36:03.524
We're actually here
to make a citizen's arrest

01:36:03.565 --> 01:36:05.055
of the entire board
of directors

01:36:05.100 --> 01:36:06.226
and the executives here.

01:36:06.268 --> 01:36:07.633
Why don't you speak
to my supervisor?

01:36:07.669 --> 01:36:09.500
- That's him right here.
- Where's he at?

01:36:09.538 --> 01:36:11.335
- In the white shirt? Blue tie?
- Yup.

01:36:11.373 --> 01:36:12.738
- That's him.
- Receding hairline?

01:36:12.774 --> 01:36:16.335
They're using the money
to buy other companies.

01:36:16.378 --> 01:36:19.040
This is our money.

01:36:19.081 --> 01:36:21.106
This is a police officer.

01:36:21.149 --> 01:36:23.276
I wanted to make a citizen's
arrest of the CEO.

01:36:23.318 --> 01:36:25.013
Mr. Blankfein.

01:36:25.554 --> 01:36:28.318
But you're here, so maybe
you could help me.

01:36:28.357 --> 01:36:31.815
- Let's do it outside.
- $170 billion of our taxpayer money.

01:36:31.860 --> 01:36:35.091
- You're not allowed in the building, sir.
- But I'm here to make an arrest.

01:36:35.130 --> 01:36:37.530
- I'm here to make an arrest.
- Make it outside, sir.

01:36:37.566 --> 01:36:38.999
I can't make it outside.
They're upstairs.

01:36:39.034 --> 01:36:40.934
I'll make an arrest, sir.

01:36:40.969 --> 01:36:42.630
You can arrest somebody?

01:36:42.671 --> 01:36:44.468
If you can arrest somebody,
I can arrest somebody.

01:36:44.506 --> 01:36:45.905
Sir, leave the building, sir.

01:36:45.941 --> 01:36:47.306
Who else do you want
to leave the building?

01:36:47.342 --> 01:36:49.139
Your cameraman and your crew.
Come on out, sir.

01:36:49.177 --> 01:36:52.044
They don't speak English.
Donde?

01:36:53.682 --> 01:36:56.344
These guys have broken
so many laws, you know?

01:36:56.385 --> 01:36:59.980
This is money.
It's theft, it's fraud.

01:37:09.498 --> 01:37:11.898
I'm gonna take it back
to the US Treasury

01:37:11.934 --> 01:37:13.731
right in this car.

01:37:13.769 --> 01:37:16.397
It's safe.
You can trust me.

01:37:19.841 --> 01:37:23.140
There's just these little hints

01:37:23.178 --> 01:37:27.615
that the unimaginable

01:37:27.649 --> 01:37:32.279
could occur, which is that...

01:37:34.723 --> 01:37:37.817
people in general

01:37:37.859 --> 01:37:40.487
in the United States
could actually

01:37:40.529 --> 01:37:43.930
become angry

01:37:43.966 --> 01:37:45.866
at the wealthy.

01:37:45.901 --> 01:37:49.393
Shame on you!
Shame on you!

01:37:49.438 --> 01:37:51.599
People who became rich in this country

01:37:51.640 --> 01:37:55.736
in the last decades
were not even making

01:37:55.777 --> 01:37:59.611
the things
that everybody loved.

01:37:59.648 --> 01:38:03.049
They were playing games

01:38:03.085 --> 01:38:05.485
that ended up actually
harming everybody.

01:38:09.291 --> 01:38:13.785
So some kind of disease
has entered into the economy.

01:38:15.397 --> 01:38:19.060
It was unusual for Americans
to turn against the rich

01:38:19.101 --> 01:38:22.332
because of the carrot that had
always been held out in front of us,

01:38:22.371 --> 01:38:25.568
that we too could be
one of them someday.

01:38:25.607 --> 01:38:28.371
People were starting not to believe that.

01:38:28.410 --> 01:38:31.106
And that frightened the rich.

01:38:31.146 --> 01:38:35.242
Because off in the distance
they heard something coming

01:38:35.283 --> 01:38:37.945
and it wasn't another dry martini.

01:38:37.986 --> 01:38:40.750
It was the friggin' people.

01:38:42.657 --> 01:38:45.023
We are ready to take this country

01:38:45.060 --> 01:38:47.221
in a fundamentally new direction.

01:38:47.262 --> 01:38:49.856
That's what's happening
in America right now.

01:38:49.898 --> 01:38:53.561
Change is what's happening
in America.

01:38:53.602 --> 01:38:55.263
Holy shit.

01:38:55.303 --> 01:38:58.295
This was not
what Wall Street wanted.

01:38:58.340 --> 01:39:00.831
What if he won?

01:39:00.876 --> 01:39:03.709
What would happen
to their way of life?

01:39:05.547 --> 01:39:07.981
So they did what they always do.

01:39:08.016 --> 01:39:10.177
They threw as much money
at him as they could.

01:39:11.887 --> 01:39:15.323
Goldman Sachs became his
number-one private contributor

01:39:15.357 --> 01:39:18.190
with nearly $1 million in contributions.

01:39:20.028 --> 01:39:23.623
But yet they still weren't sure
what he would do.

01:39:23.665 --> 01:39:26.566
How did he really feel about them

01:39:26.601 --> 01:39:29.071
and their way of life?

01:39:29.071 --> 01:39:32.973
My attitude is that if the economy
is good for folks from the bottom up,

01:39:33.008 --> 01:39:34.168
it's gonna be good for everybody.

01:39:37.279 --> 01:39:39.372
Senator Obama is running
to spread the wealth.

01:39:39.414 --> 01:39:41.848
Joe the Plumber said to him

01:39:41.883 --> 01:39:44.477
that plan sounded like socialism.

01:39:48.090 --> 01:39:49.614
I love America.

01:39:49.658 --> 01:39:53.458
I want to make sure it stays a democracy
and not a socialist society.

01:39:56.798 --> 01:40:00.199
I really think he's gonna bring socialism
if he gets half a chance.

01:40:00.235 --> 01:40:02.965
I don't trust Obama at all.

01:40:04.573 --> 01:40:06.541
I left Europe 4 decades ago

01:40:06.575 --> 01:40:08.839
because socialism has killed
opportunities there.

01:40:08.877 --> 01:40:12.574
"Someone is going to have to
give up a piece of their pie

01:40:12.614 --> 01:40:14.844
so someone else can have more."

01:40:14.883 --> 01:40:16.214
I want all my pie.

01:40:17.686 --> 01:40:20.587
Barack Obama is a socialist,
it's that simple.

01:40:24.426 --> 01:40:27.259
The scare campaign wasn't working.

01:40:27.295 --> 01:40:30.924
In fact, the more they called
Obama a socialist,

01:40:30.966 --> 01:40:34.026
the more he went ahead in the polls.

01:40:34.069 --> 01:40:36.765
And by using the word so much,

01:40:36.805 --> 01:40:41.071
it made a new generation curious
about what that was.

01:40:41.109 --> 01:40:43.737
For instance, few of them knew

01:40:43.778 --> 01:40:46.474
there was actually a socialist
in the United States Senate.

01:40:46.515 --> 01:40:49.746
Of course he was from
the gay state of Vermont.

01:40:51.186 --> 01:40:52.881
You say that you're a socialist.
Tell me what that means.

01:40:52.921 --> 01:40:54.786
I'm a democratic socialist,

01:40:54.823 --> 01:40:57.553
which means that the function
of government is to represent

01:40:57.592 --> 01:40:59.025
middle income and working people

01:40:59.060 --> 01:41:01.426
rather than just the wealthy
and the powerful.

01:41:01.463 --> 01:41:03.328
One of the things that we've done here,

01:41:03.365 --> 01:41:06.163
we've become very religious
in worshipping greed.

01:41:06.201 --> 01:41:08.533
We put on the front pages
of the magazines

01:41:08.570 --> 01:41:10.162
guys who have made
billions of dollars.

01:41:10.205 --> 01:41:12.833
We ignore the cops, the firemen,
the teachers, the nurses

01:41:12.874 --> 01:41:16.071
who every day are doing so much
in improving the lives of people.

01:41:16.111 --> 01:41:17.510
We've got to change our value system.

01:41:18.146 --> 01:41:20.310
That doesn't sound too bad.

01:41:20.348 --> 01:41:24.409
I mean, it sounds like something
maybe we should try.

01:41:24.452 --> 01:41:26.147
Within a few months,

01:41:26.188 --> 01:41:28.247
the Rasmussen poll reported

01:41:28.290 --> 01:41:30.884
that only 37% of young adults

01:41:30.926 --> 01:41:33.724
now favor capitalism over socialism.

01:41:33.762 --> 01:41:37.095
I hope the economy will...

01:41:39.401 --> 01:41:42.302
At 11:00 we project Barack Obama

01:41:42.337 --> 01:41:44.965
President-Elect
of the United States of America.

01:42:18.673 --> 01:42:21.107
Just 2 years earlier

01:42:21.142 --> 01:42:23.337
had anyone predicted
this moment,

01:42:23.378 --> 01:42:25.938
they would have been
considered crazy.

01:42:27.215 --> 01:42:29.308
But that's how fast
things change.

01:42:31.987 --> 01:42:34.478
It was in an instant

01:42:34.522 --> 01:42:38.151
a farewell to the old America.

01:42:41.162 --> 01:42:44.791
The country
was electrified by his victory.

01:42:44.833 --> 01:42:47.666
And suddenly people
were inspired

01:42:47.702 --> 01:42:50.572
to do things they never
would have done before.

01:42:51.473 --> 01:42:53.202
Like the sheriff in Detroit

01:42:53.241 --> 01:42:56.039
who decided it was time
to break the law

01:42:56.077 --> 01:42:58.170
in order to help the people.

01:42:58.213 --> 01:43:00.238
Doesn't it seem kind of strange to you

01:43:00.282 --> 01:43:03.547
they would seek a government bailout?
I thought that's not what they do.

01:43:03.585 --> 01:43:06.679
1-0-1 radio.

01:43:06.721 --> 01:43:10.282
I thought the free market
is you sink or swim.

01:43:10.325 --> 01:43:13.726
I just saw them sink
and cry like babies

01:43:13.762 --> 01:43:16.322
for assistance from everybody else.

01:43:17.499 --> 01:43:21.629
Today I will be stopping
all mortgage foreclosure sales

01:43:21.670 --> 01:43:23.331
in Wayne County.

01:43:23.371 --> 01:43:27.000
I cannot in clear conscience
allow anymore families

01:43:27.042 --> 01:43:29.567
to lose their homes
through foreclosure sales.

01:43:29.611 --> 01:43:32.375
What must the banks have thought

01:43:32.414 --> 01:43:35.474
seeing the law that was set up
to protect their interests

01:43:35.517 --> 01:43:37.246
being subverted?

01:43:37.285 --> 01:43:40.277
Do you think the free market
has failed Detroit?

01:43:40.322 --> 01:43:43.553
Well, I mean, I think that the free market
failed the country.

01:43:43.591 --> 01:43:45.860
You know, this is crazy.

01:43:45.860 --> 01:43:47.828
Neighborhoods that are
completely destroyed

01:43:47.862 --> 01:43:50.194
because too many homes
have been foreclosed.

01:43:50.231 --> 01:43:53.291
And then you wonder,
is this really America

01:43:53.335 --> 01:43:55.394
or is this a third-world country?

01:43:55.437 --> 01:43:56.927
Exactly what are we doing here?

01:43:56.971 --> 01:44:01.101
Until things get so bad that people
can do nothing but protest,

01:44:01.142 --> 01:44:03.110
and then those
are called revolutions.

01:44:03.144 --> 01:44:07.137
And sometimes revolutions begin

01:44:07.182 --> 01:44:08.410
in unlikely places.

01:44:08.450 --> 01:44:10.315
Wake up.

01:44:10.352 --> 01:44:12.013
Living in the back of a truck

01:44:12.053 --> 01:44:16.251
after a bank foreclosed on
the home they had owned for 22 years,

01:44:16.291 --> 01:44:19.692
the Trody family of Miami,
with the help of their neighbors,

01:44:19.728 --> 01:44:22.162
took matters into their own hands.

01:44:22.197 --> 01:44:25.189
On behalf of this family
and this community,

01:44:25.233 --> 01:44:28.669
we liberate this home for this family.

01:44:28.703 --> 01:44:30.603
Cut the sign down.
Take it off.

01:44:31.238 --> 01:44:32.902
Yay!

01:44:32.941 --> 01:44:35.671
When I say community,
y'all say power.

01:44:35.710 --> 01:44:38.757
- Community!
- Power!

01:44:39.481 --> 01:44:42.555
- Community!
- Power!

01:44:42.884 --> 01:44:45.250
It wasn't long before
the guy from the bank

01:44:45.286 --> 01:44:47.481
who had evicted them came back.

01:44:47.522 --> 01:44:49.251
See this?

01:44:49.290 --> 01:44:50.951
I want you to go ahead
and take a picture of that.

01:44:50.992 --> 01:44:53.392
You're trespassing.

01:44:53.428 --> 01:44:55.953
We did an eviction here and the people
went back inside the property.

01:44:55.997 --> 01:44:58.659
Yes.
So I need police assistance.

01:44:58.700 --> 01:45:00.258
When all these houses are empty

01:45:00.301 --> 01:45:02.701
the value of everybody
else's house goes down.

01:45:02.737 --> 01:45:05.831
So if you can keep
these people in this house

01:45:05.874 --> 01:45:08.104
that will help not only them...

01:45:08.143 --> 01:45:11.112
So you see, the situation is that
the people--

01:45:11.146 --> 01:45:13.137
if the bank lets them go back inside,

01:45:13.181 --> 01:45:16.673
then the bank misses the opportunity
to sell the house to somebody else.

01:45:16.718 --> 01:45:19.346
The banks are selling
so many houses right now.

01:45:19.387 --> 01:45:22.879
Well, if the bank lets everybody
get back inside the house for free--

01:45:22.924 --> 01:45:24.858
Then people will have places to live.

01:45:24.893 --> 01:45:27.623
People fighting back
was an unusual sight.

01:45:27.662 --> 01:45:30.688
So 9 police cars
responded to the call.

01:45:30.732 --> 01:45:32.723
Considering the neighborhood,

01:45:32.767 --> 01:45:34.997
the response time
was impressive.

01:45:35.036 --> 01:45:36.936
- You are not in charge.
- I'm not saying I'm in charge.

01:45:36.971 --> 01:45:39.462
I'm saying she doesn't want to be isolated.
You don't have to answer any questions.

01:45:39.507 --> 01:45:41.702
You don't have to say
anything to them, okay?

01:45:41.743 --> 01:45:43.643
But the Trodys stood their ground.

01:45:43.678 --> 01:45:46.272
We don't have nowhere else to go.

01:45:46.314 --> 01:45:49.215
- This was the backup plan.
- We're forced to live inside of a truck.

01:45:49.250 --> 01:45:52.219
This was our plan B.
We don't have no plan C.

01:45:52.253 --> 01:45:54.721
That is our grandma and it's not right.

01:45:54.756 --> 01:45:57.247
She's been in this house for 22 years
and y'all gonna put her out?

01:45:57.292 --> 01:45:59.283
How do you feel putting people
out of their homes

01:45:59.327 --> 01:46:01.454
every single frickin' day?

01:46:01.496 --> 01:46:03.896
You should rather be home
instead of do something like that.

01:46:03.932 --> 01:46:07.265
Where is the money the federal
government put in the bank?

01:46:07.302 --> 01:46:11.261
We should be telling you that you're
trespassing because this is our house.

01:46:17.612 --> 01:46:20.911
<i>* Rooted like a tree,
rooted like a tree</i>

01:46:20.949 --> 01:46:23.440
<i>* We are here</i>

01:46:23.485 --> 01:46:26.454
<i>* Stand up strong...</i>

01:46:26.488 --> 01:46:29.048
Let's go.

01:46:29.090 --> 01:46:31.115
- We did good. We did good.
- All right.

01:46:31.159 --> 01:46:34.458
The police and the man
from the bank were sent packing.

01:46:34.496 --> 01:46:36.691
Ain't no power
like the power of the people.

01:46:36.731 --> 01:46:38.995
And the power of the people don't stop.
Say what?

01:46:39.033 --> 01:46:41.661
Ain't no power
like the power of the people.

01:46:41.703 --> 01:46:44.263
And the power of the people don't stop.
Say what?

01:46:44.305 --> 01:46:46.967
Don't leave your home.

01:46:47.008 --> 01:46:48.373
Because you know what?

01:46:48.409 --> 01:46:50.673
When those companies say
they have your mortgage,

01:46:50.712 --> 01:46:53.647
unless you have a lawyer
that can put his finger

01:46:53.681 --> 01:46:56.172
or her finger on that mortgage,
you don't have that mortgage.

01:46:56.217 --> 01:47:00.176
And you're gonna find that they can't find
the paper up there on Wall Street.

01:47:00.221 --> 01:47:04.214
So I say to the American people,
you be squatters in your own homes.

01:47:04.259 --> 01:47:06.784
Don't you leave
in Ohio and Michigan,

01:47:06.828 --> 01:47:08.989
in Indiana and Illinois
and all these other places

01:47:09.030 --> 01:47:11.123
where our people are being
treated like chattel.

01:47:11.165 --> 01:47:14.328
And this Congress is stymied.

01:47:15.703 --> 01:47:18.501
It's not every day you get
to see a member of Congress

01:47:18.540 --> 01:47:21.276
encouraging open rebellion.

01:47:21.276 --> 01:47:23.506
Back in Chicago,

01:47:23.545 --> 01:47:25.911
the workers at Republic
Windows & Doors

01:47:25.947 --> 01:47:27.209
had a bright idea.

01:47:28.850 --> 01:47:31.182
They decided that on
second thought,

01:47:31.219 --> 01:47:34.416
it wasn't okay to be fired
without notice,

01:47:34.455 --> 01:47:37.549
to be denied their vacation
and severance pay

01:47:37.592 --> 01:47:40.618
and to have their
medical benefits cut off.

01:47:42.730 --> 01:47:45.426
So they came up with a plan.

01:47:45.466 --> 01:47:48.401
Tell Bank of America
and the owners of the company

01:47:48.436 --> 01:47:50.927
that it was a new day in America.

01:47:50.972 --> 01:47:52.906
They weren't going
to leave the building

01:47:52.941 --> 01:47:56.240
until they were paid
what they were owed.

01:47:56.277 --> 01:48:00.236
Yes, it was a good old fashioned
sit-down strike.

01:48:03.017 --> 01:48:05.315
We understand that perhaps

01:48:05.353 --> 01:48:08.618
some bad business deals
were made.

01:48:08.656 --> 01:48:11.887
But guess what?
We don't make business deals.

01:48:11.926 --> 01:48:14.190
We make windows and doors.

01:48:14.228 --> 01:48:16.162
Why should we be punished?

01:48:28.710 --> 01:48:31.042
The union organizers
and the workers

01:48:31.079 --> 01:48:34.776
prepared for a police assault
that was sure to come.

01:48:34.816 --> 01:48:37.444
I'm gonna take the chance.

01:48:37.485 --> 01:48:39.385
You're prepared to be arrested?

01:48:39.420 --> 01:48:41.650
I am prepared to be arrested
if it's necessary.

01:48:41.689 --> 01:48:45.648
We've been here since yesterday
and we aren't going anywhere.

01:48:45.693 --> 01:48:47.524
We are committed to this.

01:48:47.562 --> 01:48:49.894
It wasn't long before the media showed up.

01:48:49.931 --> 01:48:52.832
And given the mood of the country
toward the bailout,

01:48:52.867 --> 01:48:56.826
even the TV anchors had run out
of sympathy for the banks.

01:48:56.871 --> 01:49:00.602
In Chicago, a group of factory workers
watched like the rest of us

01:49:00.642 --> 01:49:03.270
as taxpayers bailed out
the financial industry.

01:49:03.311 --> 01:49:06.576
Now these laid-off workers
are demanding Bank of America

01:49:06.614 --> 01:49:09.310
spend some of its
bailout money on them.

01:49:09.350 --> 01:49:11.443
It says "Bank Robbers of America."

01:49:11.486 --> 01:49:14.649
Look, if we the taxpayers
are going to provide

01:49:14.689 --> 01:49:17.681
a bailout for companies
like Bank of America,

01:49:17.725 --> 01:49:20.592
then the least they can do
is use those funds

01:49:20.628 --> 01:49:23.119
on American workers
and companies.

01:49:23.164 --> 01:49:26.292
$25 billion to Bank of America.

01:49:26.334 --> 01:49:28.700
How do people sleep at night
when they act like that?

01:49:28.736 --> 01:49:30.328
I don't get it.

01:49:30.371 --> 01:49:32.271
Because what's the point
of bailing them out

01:49:32.306 --> 01:49:34.968
if there aren't any jobs?

01:49:35.009 --> 01:49:37.534
The strike went on day after day.

01:49:37.578 --> 01:49:40.342
The police had not yet come.

01:49:40.381 --> 01:49:43.179
But the son of a Chicago
steelworker did.

01:49:43.217 --> 01:49:47.381
He just also happened to be
the bishop in Chicago.

01:49:47.422 --> 01:49:49.413
Ladies and gentlemen,

01:49:49.457 --> 01:49:51.652
I am Bishop James Wilkowski.

01:49:51.693 --> 01:49:54.890
I know that you are all undergoing

01:49:54.929 --> 01:49:56.954
a great trial.

01:49:56.998 --> 01:49:59.728
You are teaching

01:49:59.767 --> 01:50:02.133
to our young people

01:50:02.170 --> 01:50:04.195
that it is just

01:50:04.238 --> 01:50:07.799
to challenge
that which is unfair.

01:50:08.843 --> 01:50:12.939
I grew up on the far southeast
side of Chicago

01:50:12.980 --> 01:50:14.709
and I saw what happened

01:50:14.749 --> 01:50:18.082
when all the steel mills
disappeared.

01:50:18.119 --> 01:50:20.986
And I saw the impact that it had

01:50:21.022 --> 01:50:22.785
on families.

01:50:22.824 --> 01:50:24.724
But this time

01:50:24.759 --> 01:50:26.818
we are with you.

01:50:26.861 --> 01:50:29.796
And we will not abandon you.

01:50:29.831 --> 01:50:31.822
In the name of the Father
and the Son

01:50:31.866 --> 01:50:33.493
and the Holy Spirit.
Amen.

01:50:33.534 --> 01:50:35.102
The body of Christ.

01:50:37.805 --> 01:50:39.332
The body of Christ.

01:50:41.976 --> 01:50:43.500
The body of Christ.

01:50:45.847 --> 01:50:48.645
When it comes to the situation

01:50:48.683 --> 01:50:52.084
here in Chicago
with the workers

01:50:52.120 --> 01:50:55.988
who are asking for the benefits
and payments

01:50:56.023 --> 01:50:58.719
that they have earned,
I think they're absolutely right.

01:51:02.330 --> 01:51:05.595
What's happening to them
is reflective of what's happening

01:51:05.633 --> 01:51:07.601
across this economy.

01:51:07.635 --> 01:51:10.263
He said, "What's happening to them
is reflective of what's happening..."

01:51:10.304 --> 01:51:12.238
He said what is happening to those workers

01:51:12.273 --> 01:51:14.867
is reflective to what's happening
across this economy.

01:51:14.909 --> 01:51:17.776
I was watching Obama's press
conference this morning.

01:51:17.812 --> 01:51:20.110
I just got out of bed and decided

01:51:20.148 --> 01:51:22.878
the best thing I could do
was to feed people.

01:51:22.917 --> 01:51:24.407
So I brought some food.

01:51:24.452 --> 01:51:26.750
- I brought some sandwiches.
- Good.

01:51:26.788 --> 01:51:30.588
In fact, lots of Chicagoans
showed up to support the workers.

01:51:30.625 --> 01:51:32.183
The workers have become
a national symbol

01:51:32.226 --> 01:51:34.251
for thousands of employees
laid off across the country.

01:51:34.295 --> 01:51:36.525
The sit-in has grabbed
the attention of politicians

01:51:36.564 --> 01:51:40.193
who believe it exemplifies an imbalance
between a Wall Street

01:51:40.234 --> 01:51:44.034
that gets government help
and a Main Street that gets the shaft.

01:51:44.071 --> 01:51:46.062
The question started to be asked:

01:51:46.107 --> 01:51:48.575
Was this is the beginnings of a worker's
revolt against Wall Street?

01:51:51.179 --> 01:51:53.306
The people united.

01:51:53.347 --> 01:51:55.406
We'll never be defeated.

01:51:55.449 --> 01:51:59.283
Bail out workers, not the banks.
Bail out workers, not the banks.

01:51:59.320 --> 01:52:03.654
Pledges of financial support and
food showed up by the truckload.

01:52:03.691 --> 01:52:07.058
It's really beyond what we had
at first initially imagined.

01:52:07.094 --> 01:52:09.892
And so now we're dreaming a little bit.

01:52:09.931 --> 01:52:12.923
We even had a conversation--
well, what if we just tried

01:52:12.967 --> 01:52:14.696
to run the factory like a cooperative?

01:52:14.735 --> 01:52:16.760
We don't have any money.
We're not capitalists.

01:52:16.804 --> 01:52:19.898
We're having those kind
of conversations

01:52:19.941 --> 01:52:22.671
and the workers are thinking about it
and it's a difficult thing

01:52:22.710 --> 01:52:24.974
'cause, you know, if you've been
told your whole life

01:52:25.012 --> 01:52:28.311
that things are the way
other people tell you they are,

01:52:28.349 --> 01:52:30.340
to be able to think
I can make it different

01:52:30.384 --> 01:52:33.478
is quite a big deal.

01:52:35.690 --> 01:52:38.352
We're all over the national news.
Everyone is watching you

01:52:38.392 --> 01:52:41.725
because they're so inspired by you.

01:52:44.398 --> 01:52:46.229
After 6 days of the sit-in

01:52:46.267 --> 01:52:49.498
Bank of America decided
enough was enough.

01:52:49.537 --> 01:52:51.732
Better to pay off
these workers now

01:52:51.772 --> 01:52:55.139
and hope their little
revolution goes away.

01:52:55.176 --> 01:52:58.907
And so the bank and the company
agreed to all the worker's demands.

01:52:58.946 --> 01:53:01.847
Yes we did!
Yes we did!

01:53:01.883 --> 01:53:05.546
The average package for each worker

01:53:05.586 --> 01:53:09.454
will be very close to $6,000.

01:53:09.490 --> 01:53:12.721
But this is about more
than just money.

01:53:12.760 --> 01:53:16.218
It's about what can be achieved

01:53:16.264 --> 01:53:20.257
when workers organize
and stand up for justice.

01:53:20.301 --> 01:53:22.360
Just to fight--
fight fight fight fight fight

01:53:22.403 --> 01:53:24.769
just to get the most basic thing

01:53:24.805 --> 01:53:26.568
that people should take for granted

01:53:26.607 --> 01:53:30.407
and that's legally theirs.

01:53:30.444 --> 01:53:34.448
We just fight so hard just for
the most basic things in life.

01:53:36.751 --> 01:53:39.879
It's a fight we knew
all too well in Flint, Michigan.

01:53:39.921 --> 01:53:43.288
For it was here that my uncle
and his fellow workers

01:53:43.324 --> 01:53:46.054
first brought down the mighty
corporate interests

01:53:46.093 --> 01:53:47.754
that dominated their lives.

01:53:49.997 --> 01:53:53.398
It was the day before
New Year's Eve in 1936.

01:53:53.434 --> 01:53:56.870
Hundreds of men and women
took over the GM factories in Flint

01:53:56.904 --> 01:53:59.236
and occupied them for 44 days.

01:54:01.108 --> 01:54:04.475
They were the first union that beat
an industrial corporation.

01:54:04.512 --> 01:54:06.810
And their actions eventually resulted

01:54:06.847 --> 01:54:09.315
in the creation of a middle class.

01:54:09.350 --> 01:54:12.478
But back in these days of the Flint
sit-down strike,

01:54:12.520 --> 01:54:16.854
the police and the company thugs
were not going to just stand by.

01:54:16.891 --> 01:54:20.486
After a bloody battle one evening,
the Governor of Michigan,

01:54:20.528 --> 01:54:23.691
with the support of the President
of the United States

01:54:23.731 --> 01:54:27.531
Franklin Roosevelt,
sent in the National Guard.

01:54:27.568 --> 01:54:31.595
But the guns of the soldiers
weren't used on the workers.

01:54:31.639 --> 01:54:33.300
They were pointed at the police

01:54:33.341 --> 01:54:35.309
and the hired goons,

01:54:35.343 --> 01:54:38.870
warning them to leave
these workers alone.

01:54:40.014 --> 01:54:42.847
For Mr. Roosevelt believed
that the men inside

01:54:42.883 --> 01:54:47.047
had a right to a redress
of their grievances.

01:54:48.389 --> 01:54:51.620
7 years later,
President Roosevelt was too sick

01:54:51.659 --> 01:54:55.493
to go up to the Capitol and give his
annual State of the Union Address.

01:54:55.529 --> 01:54:57.360
Ladies and gentlemen,

01:54:57.398 --> 01:55:00.265
the President of the United States.

01:55:00.301 --> 01:55:04.829
It has been my custom to deliver
these annual messages in person.

01:55:04.872 --> 01:55:07.898
So he gave it from
the White House over the radio.

01:55:07.942 --> 01:55:11.002
When it was over he asked
the newsreel cameras

01:55:11.045 --> 01:55:14.105
to step into his room because he
wanted the American people

01:55:14.148 --> 01:55:17.777
to see one particular part
of his speech.

01:55:17.818 --> 01:55:21.447
The President of the United States
then took the radical step

01:55:21.489 --> 01:55:24.185
of proposing a second Bill of Rights

01:55:24.225 --> 01:55:25.624
to the Constitution.

01:55:25.659 --> 01:55:29.288
In our day certain economic truths

01:55:29.330 --> 01:55:32.527
have become accepted
as self-evident.

01:55:32.566 --> 01:55:35.126
A second Bill of Rights

01:55:35.169 --> 01:55:38.935
under which a new basis of security
and prosperity

01:55:38.973 --> 01:55:41.237
can be established for all

01:55:41.275 --> 01:55:44.972
regardless of station
or race or creed.

01:55:45.012 --> 01:55:47.810
Among these are:

01:55:47.848 --> 01:55:51.807
The right to a useful
and remunerative job;

01:55:51.852 --> 01:55:55.310
The right to earn enough to provide
adequate food

01:55:55.356 --> 01:55:56.914
and clothing and recreation;

01:55:56.957 --> 01:55:59.482
The right of every farmer

01:55:59.527 --> 01:56:01.961
to raise and sell his products

01:56:01.996 --> 01:56:05.124
at a return which will
give him and his family

01:56:05.166 --> 01:56:07.532
a decent living;

01:56:07.568 --> 01:56:11.504
The right of every businessman
large and small

01:56:11.539 --> 01:56:14.906
to trade in an atmosphere of freedom,

01:56:14.942 --> 01:56:18.639
freedom from unfair competition
and domination

01:56:18.679 --> 01:56:21.807
by monopolies at home or abroad;

01:56:21.849 --> 01:56:25.307
The right of every family
to a decent home;

01:56:25.352 --> 01:56:28.981
The right to adequate medical care

01:56:29.023 --> 01:56:32.925
and the opportunity to achieve
and enjoy good health;

01:56:32.960 --> 01:56:36.293
The right to adequate protection

01:56:36.330 --> 01:56:39.731
from the economic fears
of old age,

01:56:39.767 --> 01:56:42.258
sickness, accidents

01:56:42.303 --> 01:56:44.134
and unemployment;

01:56:44.171 --> 01:56:47.231
The right to a good education.

01:56:47.274 --> 01:56:51.677
All of these rights spell security.

01:56:51.712 --> 01:56:54.738
And after this war is won,

01:56:54.782 --> 01:56:58.149
we must be prepared
to move forward

01:56:58.185 --> 01:57:01.279
in the implementation
of these rights

01:57:01.322 --> 01:57:05.088
to new goals of human happiness
and wellbeing.

01:57:05.126 --> 01:57:09.620
For unless there is security
here at home,

01:57:09.663 --> 01:57:14.498
there cannot be lasting peace
in the world.

01:57:23.944 --> 01:57:27.243
Roosevelt would be dead
in little over a year.

01:57:30.050 --> 01:57:33.383
He would not live to see
the end of the war.

01:57:33.420 --> 01:57:37.254
Nor would there be any enactment
of his new Bill of Rights.

01:57:44.732 --> 01:57:47.724
Had he lived and succeeded,

01:57:47.768 --> 01:57:50.100
every American,
regardless of race,

01:57:50.137 --> 01:57:53.265
would have had a right
to a decent job...

01:57:56.210 --> 01:57:57.802
a livable wage...

01:58:00.381 --> 01:58:01.780
universal health care...

01:58:03.817 --> 01:58:05.546
a good education...

01:58:07.988 --> 01:58:10.149
an affordable home...

01:58:12.293 --> 01:58:14.557
a paid vacation...

01:58:18.365 --> 01:58:20.993
and an adequate pension.

01:58:23.837 --> 01:58:26.431
None of this would come to pass.

01:58:28.509 --> 01:58:32.843
No American would be
guaranteed any of this.

01:58:36.450 --> 01:58:39.078
But the people of Europe and Japan

01:58:39.119 --> 01:58:41.815
got every one of these rights.

01:58:41.855 --> 01:58:44.517
How did that happen?

01:58:44.558 --> 01:58:49.291
After the war, the people
of Roosevelt's administration

01:58:49.330 --> 01:58:52.299
went overseas
to help rebuild Europe.

01:58:52.333 --> 01:58:56.326
During this time new constitutions
were written

01:58:56.370 --> 01:59:00.830
for the defeated nations
of Germany, Italy and Japan.

01:59:00.874 --> 01:59:03.570
The Italian constitution

01:59:03.611 --> 01:59:06.580
guaranteed all women equal rights.

01:59:06.614 --> 01:59:09.412
And this was 1947.

01:59:09.450 --> 01:59:13.614
The German constitution
said that the state has the right

01:59:13.654 --> 01:59:17.090
to take over property
and the means of production

01:59:17.124 --> 01:59:19.024
for the common good.

01:59:19.059 --> 01:59:22.119
And here's what we wrote up
for the Japanese.

01:59:22.162 --> 01:59:25.563
All workers have a right
to organize into a union.

01:59:25.599 --> 01:59:29.433
And academic freedom
is guaranteed.

01:59:29.470 --> 01:59:32.337
For the next 65 years

01:59:32.373 --> 01:59:34.432
we would not become the country

01:59:34.475 --> 01:59:36.375
that Roosevelt wanted us to be.

01:59:37.544 --> 01:59:41.207
Instead, we became this...

01:59:48.789 --> 01:59:51.485
I remember thinking
during the Katrina flood,

01:59:51.525 --> 01:59:53.459
"Why is it always the poor

01:59:53.494 --> 01:59:55.325
who have to suffer the misery?

01:59:55.362 --> 01:59:57.796
Why isn't it ever Bernie Madoff
up on the roof

01:59:57.831 --> 01:59:59.526
